<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Peace-Building to Be Priority in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Peace-building must be
the common focus of Liberia and its partners in the international
community, Kofi Annan, the U.N. Secretary-General, stressed here
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Fourth Ministerial Meeting of the Special
Conference on Liberia which was held today at the headquarters of
the United Nations, the U.N. chief said much had sacrificed in the
effort to bring peace to Liberia - in lives, in effort and in
resources.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the primary responsibility for
ensuring that conflict was not re-ignited in Liberia necessarily
rested with the Liberian government.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief commended President Taylor for the constructive
and statesmanlike manner in which he had begun to lay the
foundations for long-term peace, reconciliation and development in
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Annan also acknowledged and applauded the formation in Liberia
of a broad-based and inclusive Government, as well as the
expressed commitment of the New President to promote the
protection of human rights and respect for the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Annan said, the international community must do
all it could to ensure that the conditions for conflict did not
return. It must demonstrate the spirit of cooperation. generosity
and goodwill towards Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that Liberia was facing a long and difficult
road. Economic activities remained modest. Much of the population
remained displaced. Most of the demobilized fighters were yet to
be absorbed in reintegration programs. And basic institutions
and services were not yet fully operational. The Impact on Liberia
of the situation in Sierra Leone also remained a source of
concern.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Liberian Government and the international
society to work together to address the challenges facing Liberia
and ensure the success of the peace process in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
