<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Firms Urged to Be Eco-friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A noted industrialist today
urged Zimbabwean companies to manufacture environmentally
friendly products if they are to continue exporting to the
lucrative European market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing journalists, Director of Zimbabwe Trade Peter
Johnstone said the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries and
Zimbabwe Trade were jointly organizing workshops on productivity,
environment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The workshops would be held from October 29 to 31, aimed at
raising awareness among Zimbabwean industries of the new
challenges and opportunities in the field of product related
eco-requirements and increasing co-efficience in the production
process.
</P>
<P>
''Zimbabwean exporters have to take environmental requirements
on export markets, particularly in Europe, seriously if they want
to increase their market shares,'' said Johnstone, also Director
of the Export Processing Zones.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, he said, had the necessary infrastructure of export
promotion, standardization, quality control and certification
organizations to gain an image as an eco-conscious country where
buyers from Europe could find reliable suppliers for the new and
expanding green market niche.
</P>
<P>
''Adjusting to the new requirements will not impair the
competitiveness of Zimbabwean industries but increase it. On the
other hand, as suppliers of higher quality goods meeting the new
eco-criteria, they will be able to demand higher prices for their
exports,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The new focus on eco-management, he said, could lead to
increased efficiency and productivity in turn resulting in
reduced costs and harmful impacts of industrial production on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
He stressed employment creation was a priority in Zimbabwe if
the current downward trend toward poverty was to be reversed and
economic growth and stability were to be fostered.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve significant gains, he said, industrial
expansion had to be based on increasing export in the region and
to the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
