<HEADLINE> Southeastern European Defense Ministers Meet in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers from seven
southeastern European nations gathered here today to discuss the
integration of the Euro-Atlantic security structure and military
cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov, who is also
Commander-in-Chief of Bulgaria's Armed Forces, also attended the
opening ceremony, together with Italian Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta and U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The president said he hopes that such meetings will help
countries in the region cooperate in restructuring and modernizing
the armed forces and in building joint military formations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the second of its kind for nations not granted
pre-approval for entering the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) at the military alliance's Madrid summit in July.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Stoyanov said he is confident that his
country would meet all the criteria for NATO membership by the
spring of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. defense head Cohen said after a separate
meeting with Stoyanov that Bulgaria has made good progress in
military reforms.
</P>
<P>
He also said Bulgaria is "very high" on the list of nations
which are waiting for the NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Most of the seven southeastern European countries, namely
Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia, Romania, Slovenia and
Turkey, participated in the Partnership for Peace program,
launched by NATO in 1994 to help foster ties with its former
Warsaw Pact adversaries and other neutral countries.
</P>
<P>
NATO Assistant Secretary General for Political Affairs Klaus
Peter Kleiber, who greeted the Sofia meeting on behalf of NATO,
said that cooperation within the Partnership for Peace initiative
is equally important. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
