<HEADLINE> More Leprosy Patients Appear in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 640 new leprosy
patients have been identified in the nine districts of far-western
Nepal during the last fiscal year which ended on July 14, the
official RSS news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 485 patients have been cured and another 1,123 are
undergoing treatment in the far-western development region, the
agency quoted the Netherlands Leprosy Relief Association, an
international non-governmental organization, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of leprosy in the region has dropped from 12 out
of 10,000 people five years ago to 5.5 in the last fiscal year,
the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 leprosy patients have registered for treatment
throughout the Himalayan kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The government of Nepal and the World Health Organization are
making joint efforts to eradicate leprosy in Nepal by 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
