<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Urges SAARC Countries to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif called on the member states of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) to involve their people in
bilateral and multi-lateral economic and political cooperation
between them.
</P>
<P>
"We must now ensure the participation of South Asian people
themselves in the process of regional cooperation and make our
institutions more accessible and more relevant to our people,"
Sharif said today in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest city, while
inaugurating a 3-day SAARC Law Conference.
</P>
<P>
South Asian cooperation has emerged as an important dimension
in the foreign policy of each of the seven member states of SAARC
as the world is increasingly moving towards regional groupings,
Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, founded in December 1985 and comprises Bangladesh,
India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Bhutan and Maldives, is the
world's largest regional grouping in terms of population and
potential, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he observed, it is a grouping of developing countries
where a large number of people are still living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
"We must give priority to the issues that actually affect the
lives of our people and SAARC will be of relevance to them only to
the extent that we succeed in resolving such issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called for the establishment of
professional, intellectual, technical and cultural links between
people of SAARC states and continued exchange of thoughts and
ideas to deal with old problems that have lingered as well as the
new ones that may emerge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
