<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign-Asset Reporting Rule Stalled in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government has
shelved its controversial foreign-asset reporting rule for at
least a year under pressure from the province of British Columbia
(B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The rule requiring all Canadian citizens to report foreign
assets over 100,000 dollars (72,000 USD) was to have taken effect
in April of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Finance Minister Paul Martin and Revenue Minister Herb
Dhaliwal announced Thursday in Vancouver that the rule will be
delayed for a year.
</P>
<P>
Reports said today that the two ministers have also asked the
auditor-general to study the rule and come up with alternatives by
May 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Federal tax officials have said that the law was designed to
bring fairness to the tax system and make it easier to uncover tax
cheats.
</P>
<P>
Yet, since it was announced in March 1996, the rule set off a
torrent of protest in B.C.'s Asian immigrant community and
incurred criticism from tax accountants across the country.
</P>
<P>
"The perception here on the West Coast was that it was
anti-Asian," said Robert Fairweather, chairman of the Vancouver
Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
"This provision, which had never been properly explained by the
government, had created the perception that we don't want people
to come here, that we put hurdles in their way that would make
them conclude there are better places to emigrate to, like
Australia, New Zealand and the U.S.," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The revenue minister conceded that the government has to be
sensitive to concern that tougher rules could scare off potential
immigrants or lead people to shift money out of Canada.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the government remains committed to ensuring
that all Canadians pay their share of taxes and pay them on
worldwide income.
</P>
<P>
Vancouver lawyer Mason Loh, one of the leaders of the move
against the rule, insisted that the damage will continue during
the one-year delay period. Scrapping the law will be the only
answer, he said.
</P>
<P>
The delay came after an organized lobbying campaign against the
rule that was centred mainly in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
A large Asian community was reported to be at the forefront of
the effort; business groups such as the Vancouver Board of Trade
also became involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
