<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Link Between Rival Cypriot Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States has suggested
that Cyprus' Greek and Turkish communities establish trade links
as a step towards reconciliation on their divided eastern
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The idea was put forward by Richard Holbrooke,
U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus, during a meeting in New
York with Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, Cyprus News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 Dayton accords that ended a
three-and-half year ethnic war in Bosnia-Herzegovina, was quoted
as saying that "if the borders between the two parts of Cyprus
opened up for international business, it would be mutually
beneficial."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke pointed out "many peoples and countries have trade
when they do not have their political differences settled,"
adding that such business dealings would help increase the per
capita income of the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official said it is up to the two sides on the island
to work out the details of the idea.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will be co-convener of a business conference later
this month in Brussels to promote economic cooperation among
businessmen from Cyprus, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides said Thursday before his
departure for New York that he will discuss the possibility of
U.S. investments in Cyprus when he meets Holbrooke in New York.
</P>
<P>
He will be joined by Finance Minister Christodoulos
Christodoulou and Central Bank Governor Afxentis Afxentiou, as
well as U.S. business leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Radio reported Thursday that the business meeting was
arranged at Holbrooke's initiative. His idea is that business
could play a role in efforts to ease tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. businessmen are urged to participate in joint ventures
between Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Cyprus' House of Representatives
debated Thursday a government bill which seeks to legalize trade
across the Green Line dividing the island under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north and
Greek Cypriot-dominated south in 1974 when Turkish troops landed
and took over the 37 percent of the island following a short-lived
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has maintained a boycott of the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" since its
unilateral declaration of independence in 1983. It has also
striven to prevent trade between the breakaway state and the rest
of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
