<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans' Gratuities Still Headache for Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's 63.857 billion
Dollars or six billion U.S. Dollars, still at the ratification
process in parliament, will have to be juggled to squeeze in
unbudgeted lump-sum gratuities to be paid to ex-freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to do a juggling act, but I must confess this is
a serious problem," Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa told
journalists today.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the juggling would not impact negatively on
the country.
</P>
<P>
Debate on the vote allocations for the various ministries
would continue in parliament despite the fact that it was now
obvious there would be changes made to whatever the house would
have ratified.
</P>
<P>
Laying down conditions for continued support for the second
phase of the structural adjustment program, the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank have said support would continue
once financing of the war veteran gratuity was resolved.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of nationwide demonstrations by ex-fighters
complaining of neglect, President Robert Mugabe undertook to pay
each of the estimated 70,000 ex-guerillas a lump-sum gratuity of
50,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (4,300 U.S. Dollars) by December at an
estimated cost of 3.5 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (310 million
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ex-fighters would, as from next January, be
entitled to a monthly pension of 2,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (160
U.S. Dollars), including free health and education for their
families.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said, "We would need to look at some cuts
with both recurrent and capital expenditure, and we would also
look at other sources like the outside financial markets."
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said specific areas where the government would cut had
not been identified yet.
</P>
<P>
He said the award to the war veterans who waged Zimbabwe's
guerrilla warfare which culminated in independence in 1980 was
made to quell a volatile situation. Zimbabwe had to incur the
extra cost for the benefit of social stability.
</P>
<P>
Asked if his ministry was consulted in arriving at the high
figures, the minister said, "the issue was brought to cabinet and
was discussed there. Social stability has a cost."  
</P>
</TEXT>
