<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Negotiator: Israeli Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official has
warned that if Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu persists
in his settlement policy, he would find no one to go on the peace
talks with him.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local Government in the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Saeb Erekat made the remark during an interview
with the Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio today just before the start
of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, also a key negotiator with Israelis, said the 34
provisions of the interim stage agreement would be discussed
during the talks due in Washington next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The second stage of the talks that are scheduled to be held
between October 13 and 19 will deal with the Israeli unilateral
moves such as the settlement expansion and the confiscation of the
Palestinian lands, Erekat added.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also define a deadline for the work of the nine
committees' charges with carrying out the provisions of the
interim stage agreement of the Palestinian autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official urged that Israel should implement the
established agreements. Netanyahu has to choose either pursuing the
talks as means of establishing peace or continuing the settlement
expansion and imposing fait accompli, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process has been in a crisis
since March when Israel started the construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. The situation was aggravated in
two suicide bombing attacks against Israelis in Jerusalem in late
July and early September, killing a total of 25 people.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks were revived following the visit to the region
by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
