<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Killed in Italian Envoy Car Accident in Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 3 (Xinhua) -- At least two people were
killed and seven others wounded after one of the three vehicles
escorting Italian envoy to Somalia Giuseppe Cassini overturned,
witnesses said today.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred near Lego village, 130 km southwest of
the capital, via Baidoa road late last night.
</P>
<P>
According to an eyewitness, when the first Toyota pick-up
travelling on high speed swerved, one of the tyres of the truck
exploded, making the driver lose control of the vehicle so that
the car turned over, killing one of its occupants on the spot and
wounding eight others.
</P>
<P>
All wounded were rushed back to Mogadishu for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Despite the accident, the Italian Envoy to Somalia continued
his journey to Baidoa town to probe the alleged massacre there.
</P>
<P>
Baidoa has recently been a focal point for the fighting
between Hussein Mohamed Aidid's forces and those of the Rahanwein
Army (RRA) over the control of the region.
</P>
<P>
Before returning to Mogadishu this afternoon, Cassini has this
morning toured the main hospital of the town, the main market and
several other parts of Baidoa where he met different community
figures including Hussein Aidid's representatives in Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
There is no official word yet from Cassini himself whether
there has been any trace for the alleged massacre in the area.
However, at the time of his visit, the troubled areas surrounding
Baidoa were calm, and there were no reports of any violence.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the Italian diplomat was made after Hussein Aidid
accepted the envoy's tour of Baidoa town where, according to the
RRA, an alleged gross human rights violation was committed by the
forces of Hussein Aidid in and around Baidoa early in the week.
</P>
<P>
RRA officials in North Mogadishu have reportedly asked the
envoy to investigate the alleged mass killing in which, according
to them, more than 260 people were killed and 19 villages were
set on fire.
</P>
<P>
Cassini arrived in Mogadishu Monday, Two months after his
mission of reconciling Mogadishu's factions failed following the
visit of Mr. Rino Serri, Italy's Under-Secretary of Foreign
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Cassini has during this week held separate talks with Ali
Mahdi Mohamed, leader of the north Mogadishu faction and Hussein
Mohamed Aidid, head of the south Mogadishu faction, in Mogadishu
over how to promote the reconciliation efforts between the
Somalis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
