<HEADLINE> Canada's Bank Rate May Rise Again, Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada may further
raise its bank rate in coming months to ward off inflation,
according to governor Gordon Thiessen.
</P>
<P>
"The current level of interest rate is highly stimulative and
it is going to have to go up," the bank chief was quoted as saying
by reports today.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came a day after the central bank raised its
overnight lending rate by 25 basis points to 3.75 percent, the
second rate hike since June.
</P>
<P>
"How rapidly is going to depend on just how much momentum there
is in this economy and how quickly we approach full capacity,"
Thiessen said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that low inflation is his priority, because it
contributes to a more stable and productive economy.
</P>
<P>
The bank chief said he wants to prevent a return to the
boom-and-bust economy of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Canada's economy can withstand interest rates increases, he
maintained.
</P>
<P>
"I think consumers are increasingly feeling better, so I don't
think we have the need for the extremely low interest rates we had
before," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
