<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Urges Donors' Coop in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) has advised international organizations intending
to deliver humanitarian aid to Sierra Leone to always clear with
it.
</P>
<P>
The call was made on Thursday in Monrovia by ECOMOG Deputy
Force Commander, Brigade-General Joe Kwateng on behalf of ECOMOG
Force Commander, Major-General Victor Malu, when a Netherlands
delegation visited the peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Brigade-General Kwateng said the request for such
organizations to get clearance from ECOMOG was in their own
interest, stressing that by liaising with ECOMOG, they would be
abreast of the situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
By letting ECOMOG know their humanitarian mission, such
organizations will also be able to get protection and assistance
from ECOMOG, especially as the only international airport in
Sierra Leone was under ECOMOG protection, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG forces went into Sierra Leone soon after the May 25
coup that overthrew the government of elected President Ahemd
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
West African leaders agreed a month ago at their summit in
Abuja to impose sanctions and embargo on Sierra Leone to force
out the military junta that seized power from Kabbah. They
authorized ECOMOG to enforce the blockade.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG jet fighters in early September bombed a vessel docked
in the port of Freetown for allegedly bringing in arms and
ammunition. But the Sierra Leonean side insisted that there was
only rice on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
