<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Conveys New Year Greetings to Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- On the occasion of the Jewish
New Year, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has conveyed greetings
to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for a year of peace,
Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak said today.
</P>
<P>
The greetings were expressed during an Arafat-Netanyahu
telephone call Thursday evening, the first conversation between
the two leaders since the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have
been suspended in March when Israel started building the
controversial Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Bazak said Arafat said happy new year to the Israeli people in
the phone call which was made during his visit in Jordanian
capital Amman.
</P>
<P>
In his reply, Netanyahu said he wished the next year would be
"a year of peace for Israelis and Palestinians, and a good year
for all residents in the region."
</P>
<P>
Their conversation coincided with the announced resumption of
the peace negotiations for next week, signaling a thaw in the
Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
United States secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who
sponsored the meeting in New York between Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen),
announced on September 29 that Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) would resume the talks on implementing the Interim
Agreement in the week of October 6.
</P>
<P>
In a new year interview with Israel Radio broadcast today,
Netanyahu welcomed the resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian
talks, terming it as "a good step forward" to advance the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that he would reach a final settlement
with the PNA if Arafat agreed to launch a consistent fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The "key element ... for advancing the peace process in the
Middle East, between us and the Palestinians, is the battle
against terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
He demanded PNA's promise of taking concrete actions to fight
terrorism, adding that the PNA had not yet done enough in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the final-status talks which have been frozen
since May last year after Netanyahu came to power, Netanyahu said
he hoped the talks would be resumed soon, and if possible
accelerated to reach a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Again, he conditioned the success of the final-status talks,
which will deal with the most sensitive issues of Jerusalem,
final borders and Palestinian refugees, on the PNA's fight
against militant Islamic groups which have been launching suicide
bombing attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Albright's appeal for a time-out of Israeli
settlement activities, Netanyahu said that Israel and the PNA had
only agreed to discuss the concept of time-out. He reiterated that
his government had a policy on settlements and would not change
it, indicating that the settlement activities will continue.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu virtually ruled out the possibility of setting up
a national unity government with the opposition Labor party,
expressing confidence that his government will gain popular
public support for its continuous efforts to fight terrorism
and provide security to its people.
</P>
<P>
The hardline Israeli leader sounded pessimistic about the
prospect of reaching peace with Syria and Lebanon. He conceded
that he had failed to find a "bridging formula" to resume
peace talks with Syria because Damascus refuses to accept the
Israeli demand for unconditional resumption of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Syria is insisting that the peace talks, frozen since March
last year, should be picked up from where they were left off with
Israel's previous Labor government -- namely on Israeli promise to
fully withdraw troops from the occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he had found any solution to pull out Israeli troops
from South Lebanon, Netanyahu blamed the unwillingness of
consecutive Lebanese governments to "exert sovereignty" over the
region for Israel's continued military presence in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
For the past 19 years, Israel has been bogged down in a
bloody guerrilla war with the Hezbollah forces in South
Lebanon. The increasing number of Israeli casualties has sparked
heated debate within the Jewish state over the necessity of
keeping the so-called South Lebanon Security Zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
