<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quelea Birds Make Great Loss to Nigerian Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Rice and millet crops worth of
two billion Naira (about 25 million U.S. Dollars) have been lost
to quelea birds in northwest Nigeria's Kebbi State, the official
News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Samaila Dabo, the state commissioner for agriculture, was
quoted as saying that about 700,000 hectares of farm land in
seven local governments was ravaged by the birds.
</P>
<P>
Quelea birds move in large numbers and could travel to long
distances within a short time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dabo stressed the need for neighboring Niger and the Republic
of Benin to co-operate so as to effectively control the invasion
of the birds.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the state government has released 8.4
million Naira (about 100,000 dollars) to fight against the birds.
</P>
<P>
Dabo also warned residents in the affected area against eating
the birds because the chemicals sprayed for their control might
pose health hazards to anyone who eats them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
