<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Ready to Start Talks with PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 3 (Xinhua) - The Islamic Resistance Movement,
or Hamas, today showed its willingness to put up with the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) which detained hundreds of
Hamas members in security cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was ready to start talks with the PNA, said Khalid
Mashiel, head of the political bureau of the anti-Israeli militant
group, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Mashiel did not say what would be discussed with the PNA, but a
demand of releasing Hamas prisoners is almost surely expected.
</P>
<P>
Mashiel was giving his first press conference at his home after
hospitalization following being attacked here by two tourists
holding forged Canadian passports on September 25. Initial
investigation showed that the attackers were members of the
Israeli security service "Mossad."
</P>
<P>
The talks with the PNA would not be held within the context of
Israeli or the United States' conditions, but within Palestinian
conditions, said Mashiel.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel and the U.S. did not really want to act in
accordance with the Oslo peace agreement reached four years ago,
so their conditions were unacceptable to Hamas, Mashiel added.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for a string of suicide
bombing attacks against Israelis for the past few months. And
Israel has constantly pressed the PNA to crack down on Hamas as a
precondition to resume negotiations and loosen sanctions on
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The peace process between the PNA and Israel has been stalled
since March this year when Israel began to build Jewish
settlements in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Arab land. Most Hamas political leaders live in
Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
