<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Recovery in Europe Gaining Pace: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The economic situation in
Europe strengthened in the Summer and firms' assessments of the
economic situation, particularly in industry, have confirmed
growing confidence in the future trend, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
This is reflected in the latest business survey results
published Friday by the European Union (EU)'s executive body, the
European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The results confirm the upturn in domestic and export demand.
Assessments of both new orders and order-book levels in industry
point to increasing demand for industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Industrial firms are becoming increasingly less pessimistic
about order-book levels. In Denmark, the Netherlands, Portugal and
Finland, they are even viewed as being relatively high by the
majority of firms.
</P>
<P>
The increased demand for industrial goods had also been
underpinned recently by more buoyant external trade. This is
reflected in industrial firms' assessments of the level of foreign
orders.
</P>
<P>
While they are still regarded, on average in the Union, as
being too low, the majority of firms in virtually all member
countries, except the United Kingdom, expect an appreciable
increase in the volume of exports.
</P>
<P>
Industrial firms' assessments regarding employment expectations
have again improved. However, an increase in staffing levels is
expected only in Denmark, Spain and Italy. Firms in other member
countries still plan to shed labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
