<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pudong Ideal Choice for Overseas Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Policy incentives and years of
development in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai have led to a
surging of overseas banks there.
</P>
<P>
The recent opening of the Shanghai Branch of the Banca
Commercial Italiana in Pudong brought the number of the overseas
banks there to 22, accounting for 43 percent of the total
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Local financial analysts say that the overseas banks have
speeded up their move to this emerging economic zone across the
Huangpu River from downtown Shanghai, mainly because the People's
Bank of China has decided this year that overseas banks in Pudong
can start Renminbi yuan business.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-February this year, nine overseas banks with yuan
business approval have moved their Shanghai branches to the
Lujiazui Financial and Trade Zone in Pudong. They include the Citi
Bank NA, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd, the Hong Kong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation, the Industrial Bank of Japan, the
Sanwa Bank and the Standard Chartered Bank.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, Pudong had only two foreign bank
branches.
</P>
<P>
Other overseas financial institutions such as investment banks
and insurance companies also joined the relocation rush.
Statistics show that more than 90 percent of the newly-approved
overseas financial institutions this year chose to settle down in
Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the Lujiazui Financial and Trade Zone has
become the first choice for overseas banks, because of its
advantageous location and favorable policies.
</P>
<P>
Other contributing factors include an accumulation of large
enterprises and markets of essential product means, improved city
infrastructures, and relatively low rent on the commercial houses
in Pudong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
