<HEADLINE> Lee Kuan Yew Urges Singapore Schools to Recruit More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
urged Singapore schools and universities to actively attract
foreign students from Asian countries so as to strengthen
relations among the nations involved and to broaden the horizons
for Singaporeans.
</P>
<P>
This will help build up solidarity with the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries, the senior minister
said at the Old Rafflesians' Association Dinner tonight.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested a quota for overseas students for Raffles
Institute, Raffles Girls School and the Raffles Junior College,
three prominent schools in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Top foreign universities come here to attract Singapore
students. So, this means schools and universities in Singapore
cannot afford to sit back, Lee pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Later in life, after those foreign students return to their
countries, they will be part of the network of influential friends
throughout the region, people who will help each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will build up an old boy network that will increase
solidarity with the ASEAN neighbors, he said. So he proposed that
the Raffles Institute, the Raffles Girls School and the Raffles
Junior College should aim for a 20 percent overseas intake yearly.
</P>
<P>
He said that there will be enough places for Singaporeans. This
extra 20 percent of high-quality overseas students will bring
benefits to the 80 percent Singaporeans, Lee stressed.
</P>
<P>
He believed foreign students will stimulate and challenge their
Singaporean counterparts to broaden their horizons.  
</P>
