<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankrupt Ventures Auctioned in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The successful sale of a
bankrupt steel venture in south China's Guangdong province has
been hailed as a sign that the city's reform of the state sector
is traveling on a more standardized course.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Special-shaped Steel Plant was sold in just more
than ten minutes at an auction, drawing a smooth close to the
first case of bankruptcy since Guangzhou began to experiment with
the modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden firm was sold to a local steel plant for 50
million yuan (6 million US dollars), much of which is expected to
be used to aid the displaced workers and the rest to pay off
debts, according to local legal officials.
</P>
<P>
The assets of the bankrupt firm were evaluated at 55 million
yuan (6.6 million US dollars), including the land-use right, the
factory buildings, machinery, and some products in stock.
</P>
<P>
Managers of the bankrupt firm said that their venture
floundered because of a bad investment, poor management and
limited understanding of market competition.
</P>
<P>
However, numbers of buyers showed an interest in the firm at
the auction, since the company is considered to be well-equipped
and its products still have great market potential.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy is an inevitable result of the market competition
and allows for sound development of the market economy, said the
local leading legal official Deng Guoji, pointing to the fact that
it phases out incompetent enterprises and redistributes the social
assets more rationally.
</P>
<P>
Starting from early 1992, a total of 36 enterprises with
different types of economic ownership in Guangzhou have petitioned
to the local courts to declare bankruptcy, and the figure has been
rising at an annual rate of over 70 percent since 1994, said Deng
Guoji.
</P>
<P>
The local court has so far investigated into 19 such cases, and
settled four. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
