<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 425 Generals Squeezed out in Russian Military Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 425 generals are going to
lose their ranks in the Russian armed forces if the Russian
military reform goes on as planned, the daily newspaper Segodnya
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an army spokesman as saying that the
numbers of generals in the army will be reduced to 1,500 from the
1,925 generals on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of generals is part of the Russian military
reform, which aims to cut the size of the armed forces by 500,000
to 1.2 million by the end of 1998 while keeping the army's combat
readiness unaffected.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the reform will first involve
personnel in the armed forces' central institutions.
</P>
<P>
The numbers of Senior Generals will be cut from the present 12
to 6, Generals from 169 to 67, Lieutenant Generals from 470 to 353
while Major Generals will be 1,072 instead of the present 1,242.
</P>
<P>
the spokesman said the country will keep only two marshals
after the reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
