<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for New Governance After 1998 Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
here today called for a new framework for governance after the
1998 polls by changing the Charter to make the country more
responsive to the challenges and needs of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"Let us insure that a new framework for governance is put in
place without further delay after the May 1998 elections by
amending the 1987 Constitution so that our people can be armed
with a fundamental law that will be responsive to their needs in
the 21st century and beyond," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the remarks when enumerating eight unfinished tasks
that have to be tackled. Other uncompleted tasks include electing
the best officials in the 1998 elections, enhancing productivity
and sustaining the country's competitiveness, celebrating the
centennial of national independence and fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
He also urged everyone to unite as a people in the fulfillment
of the urgent missions that still need to be done.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ramos' supporters tried in vain to extend the term of
the president through amending the Constitution which allows Ramos
to serve only a single term of six years.
</P>
<P>
Ramos announced that he would not run for re-election just
before the September 21 rally in which former president Corazon
Aquino warned him not to cite unfinished tasks as an excuse to
seek a second term.  
</P>
</TEXT>
