<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renovation of Famous Tibetan Buddhist Monastery Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The renovation of a famous Tibetan
Buddhist temple, the Gandain Monastery, was completed here today.
</P>
<P>
Located some 60 km to the east of Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, the Gandain Monastery is one of the three
largest monasteries in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1409 by Zong Kaba, founder of the Gellug (Yellow) Sect
of Tibetan Buddhism, the monastery was listed among
state-protected cultural relics in 1961 by the State Council,
China's cabinet, but was destroyed during the turmoil of the
Cultural Revolution period (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of reform and opening-up in the late 1970s,
China has kept funding the renovation work of the Gandain
Monastery. In 1993, the central government allocated more than 26
million yuan (3.13 million US dollars) for a comprehensive
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years and four months, more than 40 experts of
ancient architecture and over 900 workers were involved in the
grand-scale project, rebuilding an overall area of 11,192 square
meters of housing.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, more than 1,660 square meters of the monastery's
original murals were restored, and 41 kilograms of gold were used
to regild the monastery's golden roofs.
</P>
<P>
The renovation team also completed a project to send drinking
water to the monastery, which was built on mountains with an
elevation of some 4,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they helped the monks to build 29 mini solar power
stations and replace the old butter lamps in temple halls and
monks' residences with nearly 500 solar energy lights.
</P>
<P>
"The renovation project has once again proved the Communist
Party of China's adherence to its policy of freedom of religious
worship in Tibet, as well as the Party's dedication to protecting
and carrying forward the traditional culture of the Tibetans,"
said Lieque, executive vice-chairman of the Tibetan Autonomous
Regional government.
</P>
<P>
The project was declared "a fine piece of work" in today's
quality assessment. It was said that a book on the complete
process of the renovation is to be published shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
