<HEADLINE> SIDA Grants Uganda Fund to Boost Book Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Swedish International
Development Agency (SIDA) has granted Uganda 34,000 U.S. Dollars
to boost this year's national book week festival, reported Radio
Uganda today.
</P>
<P>
The festival which is being held from November 3 to 8, 1997,
is being organized by the national book week committee under the
chairmanship of James Tumusiime, the Managing Director of
Fountain Publishers and Vice Chairman of the African Publishers
network.
</P>
<P>
In an agreement signed last week between Swedish Counselor for
development cooperation in Kampala Anders Ostman and Tumusiime,
SIDA has agreed to fund most of the activities of the book week
including transport, hire of venues and publicity materials.
</P>
<P>
The festival, which is being funded together with those of
Kenya and Tanzania, is intended to focus national attention on
the importance of books and reading and to gradually link up the
three east African countries to form a regional book market.
</P>
<P>
The festival will bring together all players in the book
industry including authors, publishers, book sellers, printers,
teachers and officials of the ministries of education and sports
and gender and community development in the country.
</P>
<P>
The festival will also attracted similar organizations and
distinguished personalities from Kenya, Tanzania and Rwanda.
</P>
