<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Digs Canal in Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese workers have dug a canal
in the Three Gorges area for ships chugging through the Yangtze
River, which will be dammed early next month.
</P>
<P>
The country's navigation department today began to supervise
operation on the canal, which is 3,726 meters long, 350 meters
wide and 58 meters deep. It is said to be deeper and wider than
the Suez and Panama canals.
</P>
<P>
Starting on October 6, normal navigation will be stopped on the
main stream of the Yangtze in the dam area and all the ships
will change their courses into the canal.
</P>
<P>
The canal is capable of releasing 79,000 cubic meters of
floodwater per second.
</P>
<P>
However, engineers said that if the flow volume exceeds
20,000 cubic meters per second in the flooding season, a lock will
be used to help the navigation.
</P>
<P>
The canal will be operating for six years during the dam
construction till a permanent lock is completed in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
