<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks Compromise Over Total's Iran Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The act bans all companies throughout the world from investing
more than 40 million dollars in the oil and hydrocarbon sector of
Iran and Libya, which Washington has accused of backing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The EU has regularly expressed its opposition to the act,
saying it has extraterritorial effect such as the Helms-Burton
Act, which is aimed at punishing foreign companies doing business
in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to sign a contract to develop an oil field in
Iran is a commercial decision for Total alone. The company is
legally entitled to take such a decision," Leon Brittan,
vice-president of the European Commission, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the specter of a full-blown trade war with the EU
appears to have prompted a more conciliatory approach from the
U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the fact that the threats have failed to ward
off major investment projects has also shattered Washington's
containment policy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials now talk of looking for "greater concerted
action" with European governments on how to deal effectively with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
One possible solution would be for President Bill Clinton to
waive his right to punish Total, extract a cosmetically tougher EU
line and deny Teheran a significant tactical victory. A measure
already suggested is the EU's postponement of the return to
Teheran of its ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has confirmed the
U.S. is seeking a way out of applying sanctions against the
companies.
</P>
<P>
But she also added, "I think what France is doing is
wrong. They are injecting money into a terrorist system." 
</P>
</TEXT>
