<HEADLINE> Workers Deal with Debris in Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese workers have made
headway in dealing with leftover debris from the Three Gorges
area, as they prepare for the blocking of the Yangtze River early
next month.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the damming of the river, some 400,000 people have
been evacuated from seven countries, namely Yichang, Zigui,
Xingshan and Badong of Hubei province and Wushan, Fengjie and
Yunyang of the newly-founded Chongqing municipality, which will be
affected by the flooding.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement work has left 1.65 million square meters of
empty housing in the area, together with a large number of
toilets, warehouses, rubbish dumps, bridges, scattered graves and
cattle pens. All of this will be submerged, creating navigational
blocks and spreading pollution.
</P>
<P>
The workers have been disinfecting polluted material, or moving
it to distant and outlying sites. So far, they have dismantled
900,000 square meters of building structures, removed leftover
debris and done sanitation and anti-epidemic work in 13,000
places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
