<HEADLINE> Aid Workers Ordered to Leave Goma in E. Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. refugees agency today
said its members are ready to leave Goma in eastern part of the
Republic of Democratic Congo as Congo's Interior Ministry has
ordered them to leave.
</P>
<P>
In a press release here today, the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) said it was regrettable that the Congolese
authorities have "ordered all agencies dealing with refugees to
leave the Goma area with immediate effect."
</P>
<P>
It disclosed that the same instruction from the Ministry also
ordered the local authorities to close the border between North
Kivu and Rwanda, telling them to "expel any Rwandan refugees who
have entered the area."
</P>
<P>
In 1994, over a million Hutu refugees of Rwanda cross via Goma
into Congo Kinshasa after the massacre occurred following the
murder of its former president. About 600,000 of the refugees
returned in October last year after the Rwandan authorities said
they welcomed them to go back home.
</P>
<P>
Tribal conflicts between Hutus and Tutsis compelled the Hutus
to leave their country to avoid fighting.
</P>
<P>
L. Kabila led an uprising in October last year in eastern
Congo or former Zaire and toppled former President Mobuto Sese
Seko in March. He became President of Democratic Congo this May
under the help of the Rwandan authorities.
</P>
<P>
The release said, "we are deeply concerned about the
implications this announcement will have for Rwandan refugees who
have begun crossing the border again in recent days to avoid
renewed fighting in western Rwanda." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
