<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for South-North Dialog in Health Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
today called for South-North dialog and international cooperation
to find ways to meet the technological and financial needs of the
developing countries for the health issue.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 44th session of the
Eastern Mediterranean Regional Committee of the World Health
Organization, Khatami said that access to health for all people
was the primary responsibility of each country.
</P>
<P>
The extraterritorial nature of health and their moral and
spiritual importance demonstrated the need for broad cooperation
at world level among nations, governments, governmental and
non-governmental organizations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said such cooperation would help find solutions to the
existing problems, defuse social crises, as well as promote
international understanding and strengthen the world peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president voiced Iran's readiness to make efforts
to eradicate poverty and promote international scientific and
technological cooperation in a bid to safeguard health of the
society.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran's health development plans have been carried
out in line with the national five-year development plans and
within the general framework of Islamic social justice.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the World Health Organization Hiroshi
Nakajima warned at the meeting that major diseases as malaria and
tuberculosis had made a deadly comeback in many parts of the world
in recent years and that previous unknown diseases had spread
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
She attributed the situation to poverty, armed conflicts,
industrial pollution, budget cuts and the degradation of basic and
public health infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and specialists from 22 eastern
Mediterranean countries attending the four-day meeting will
discuss draft proposals for "Health for All in the 21st Century."
</P>
