<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Maps Lag Behind Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China's cartographers have found it
hard to keep up with the quick changes in the country's appearance.
</P>
<P>
The numbers of Chinese cities has grown from 479 to 666 in the
past several years, according to the State Statistics Bureau. And
many small cities have evolved into big ones, with the countryside
becoming urban area.
</P>
<P>
All this adds up to a big headache for map publishers. In 1995,
shortly after the Xi'an Map Publishing House came out with the
Transportation Map of the People's Republic of China, the
construction of the Beijing-Kowloon railway started.
</P>
<P>
The map has since been revised three times in three years in
line with the construction progress of the railway.
</P>
<P>
"I feel that the map cannot keep up with the changes," said Ren
Zhongnan, deputy director of the Shanxi Publications
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Just five years ago, Ren noted, a person could easily travel
across the country with a single map in hand.
</P>
<P>
New railways, highways, new ports, airports and nuclear plants,
as well as the Three Gorges Dam, are posing new challenges to
China's map-makers.
</P>
<P>
"Previously, it was our job to make a map. Today it is the
laborers who are creating the new look for the country," said Qian
Tianjiu, chief editor of the Xi'an Map Publishing House.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
