The fires, said the report, at an altitude of between 2,800
and 4,000 meters, currently pose no major threat to local
populations, but are destroying rare and endangered habitat.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. which is appealing for international help to combat
the fires, said government troops lacked adequate equipment.
</P>
<P>
There is no details however, on the cause of this latest fire.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said that the fire on Kilimanjaro was put
out on September 18 after two weeks' ravages.
</P>
<P>
Lorivole Moirana, chief warden for the Kilimanjaro National
park Authority said the fire was put out owing to concerted
efforts of the local residents and specialized fire fighting
personnel.
</P>
<P>
That fire, which affected an estimated 109 square kilometers
of bush and forest and represented 10,900 hectares of forest
cover, could have been started by campers since it started at the
Machame tourist camp, Moirana added.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is now hard hit by a drought which may enable to fire
to resume under strong winds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0070 </DOCNO>
