<HEADLINE> Courier, Gustafsson To Meet in Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Top-seed Jim Courier of the
United States set a final clash with former world number ten
Magnus Gustafsson of Sweden after winning Saturday's China Open
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Courier, former world number one, overpowered Sweden's third
seeded Thomas Johansson 6-3, 6-4, while fifth seeded
Gustafssonousted Kenneth Carlsen of Denmark 6-2, 6-4 in 69 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Courier's win was not an easy one. Johansson kept himself in
every point by returning his opponent's big shots and forcing some
long rallies.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't that easy, but I think I was a bit more solid on the
big points," Courier said.
</P>
<P>
Gustafsson, now ranked 47th in the world, played a solid match
and took the control of the contest through his powerful
forehand. Carlsen failed to overtake Gustafsson upon his big
serves as he did in his previous matches.
</P>
<P>
"I have the battle when I am concentrated through," said
Gustafsson after his win. "I am sure to beat Courier if I am
concentrated like this."
</P>
<P>
"But Courier is a player who never give up in the match," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Courier and his countryman Alex O'Brien, whose semifinal rivals
J. Eagle and A. Florent of Australia pulled out Saturday's
semifinal due to Eagle's flu, will face top seeds M. Bhupathi and
L. Paes of India in the doubles final.
</P>
<P>
Both individual and doubles finals play on Sunday. 
</P>
