<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cabinet Approves Lebanon's Austerity 1988 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beirut, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese cabinet Thursday
night approved Prime Minister Rafik Hariri's austerity budget for
1998, ending nine days of political wrangling and relaxing a run
on the U.S. dollar, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Beirut Times quoted Hariri as saying that the budget bill
put next year's expenditures at 7,925 billion Lebanese pounds
(about 4.6 billion U.S. dollars) and revenues at 4,956 billion
pounds (about 3.2 billion dollars) with a deficit of 37.46 percent
of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The figures represent nearly a 6 percent rise in expenditure
over last year's budget and a drop of more than 16 percent from
the current deficit, which is expected to be around 15 billion
dollars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The new budget ended the controversy over Hariri's previous
plan to raise 1 billion dollars for emergency development projects.
</P>
<P>
The plan was rejected by the cabinet because it included an
unpopular increase of up to 50 percent in gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
The new budget bill promises improved ways to collect taxes
and imposes additional duties on services such as car
registration, passports, and residence permits for expatriate
labor.
</P>
<P>
The budget will be debated by the parliament next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
