<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan, Kenyan Officials Meet on Border Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- High-level officials from
Uganda and Kenya held a one-day meeting on peace, security and
trade across common border Friday in Mbale district, eastern
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to set up bilateral peace monitoring
committees in their countries, Radio Uganda reported today.
</P>
<P>
Wajusi Wasieba, Ugandan State Minister for Works, Transport
and Communications, assured the Kenyan officials at the meeting
that the Uganda government and people have no hidden agenda
against its sister country, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Tension remains high in the border areas as cross-border
cattle rustling often happens. On September 20, Ugandan cattle
rustlers crossed the border in raids in northwestern Kenya,
taking away thousands of domestic animals and killing 46 Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 people have died in clashes between security
personnel and Ugandan cattle rustlers in Kenya's Turkana and
Pokot districts alone over the past three months, Kenyan paper
reports said.
</P>
<P>
But Wasieba noted, Kenya should reciprocate this assurance by
denying platforms to anti-government dissidents operating in
Nairobi in order to fulfill the east African cooperation spirit
of good neighborliness, mutual respect and economic integration.
</P>
<P>
He accused Kenya of backing Ugandan dissidents but Nairobi
denies the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting agreed that the peace monitoring
committees would meet quarterly every year starting from the end
of October or early November this year, and meet regularly when
critical issues arise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
