<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has telephoned his Indian counterpart Inder Kumar Gujral
and the two leaders agreed to "take positive steps to promote
mutual trust and confidence" between the two countries, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
In his telephone talk with Gujral on Friday, Sharif emphasized
that the two prime ministers should work to maintain a climate of
undisturbed peace to promote tranquillity and security in the
region, the officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed that mutual trust and confidence
should be promoted and positive steps should be taken to prevent
the vitiation of the atmosphere, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister also suggested to his Indian
counterpart that provocative statements should also be avoided,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the shelling incidents on the Line of Control in
Kashmir earlier this week, Sharif suggested that recurrence of
such incidents must be prevented, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Gujral said that he had ordered his
troops to stop firing, they said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif welcomed Gujral's decision and said that the Pakistani
forces would also stop firing as they were only responding to the
Indian shelling, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the need to reduce tension and to promote
peace and amity.
</P>
<P>
To this end it was necessary to hold meaningful discussions on
all the issues between the two countries, especially the core
issue of Jammu and Kashmir, he said.  
