<HEADLINE> Baltic Region Mayors Meet in St. Petersburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Mayors of major cities in the
Baltic region met today in St. Petersburg to discuss mutually
beneficial cooperation in all fields, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The mayors attending the final stage of the Baltic city mayors
conference focused on coordinating their activities in the
development of joint projects in ecology, tourism, sea and land
transportation, communications, civil security, culture and
education.
</P>
<P>
These projects, parts of a program called "The Baltic
Initiative of St. Petersburg" and proclaimed by the city
administration, are to be submitted to the European Union and
other international organizations for discussion, the report said.
</P>
<P>
St. Petersburg Governor Vladimir Yakovlev said the programs
would improve the development of the Baltic region as well as that
of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
He said the programs would help the Baltic region increase
contacts with other CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States)
countries and rapidly developing Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Mayors of 14 cities in the Baltic region as well as Berlin,
Bordeaux, Warsaw and Paris attended the conference, which followed
the first stage of the conference held in Turku, Finland, in
mid-September of this year. 
</P>
