<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Coalition Government Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's seven-month-old
coalition government headed by Lokendra Bahadur Chand collapsed
Saturday afternoon after the Lower House passed by 107-94 votes a
no-confidence motion against the government tabled by the main
opposition Nepali Congress (NC).
</P>
<P>
Though the ruling Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML) has asked all its 89 MPs to vote
against the no-confidence motion, Chand's efforts to save his
government failed after ministers tendered resignations one after
another.
</P>
<P>
One day before the vote, Chand had only five votes from his own
National Democratic Party (RPP).
</P>
<P>
The key sealing the fate of the three-party government lay in
the divisive RPP itself.
</P>
<P>
The faction led by RPP President Surya Bahadur Thapa, who asked
the NC to lodge the no-confidence motion against the government on
September 22, held a parliamentary party meeting without the
presence of its parliamentary party leader Chand and directed all
RPP MPs to vote in favor of the motion.
</P>
<P>
The minor ruling partner Nepal Sadbhavana (goodwill) Party and
other parties also decided to vote for the motion.
</P>
<P>
Surya Bahadur Thapa is expected to head the next government as
promised by the NC.
</P>
<P>
Chand's government is the most short-lived among the five
governments seen in Nepal since 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
