<HEADLINE> Liberians Warned Not to Molest Peace-keepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The force commander of the west
African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) has warned Liberian citizens
to desist from further molestation of ECOMOG soldiers or face the
consequence.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by Major-General Victor Malu, some
rogues and miscreants have formed the habit of "raising false
alarms, claiming a loss of their genitals on shaking hands with,
or being touched by their enemies".
</P>
<P>
The false alarms are being targeted at ECOMOG soldiers who
were manhandled and molested by these individuals, the Tribune
reported today.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops have been assaulted and lynched through these
false allegations, General Malu claimed, quoted by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The force further warned the trouble makers to stop their
nefarious activities or face the wrath.
</P>
<P>
"Any such future attempt to molest any ECOMOG soldier would be
strongly resisted by the force and all those involved would be
severely dealt with," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the force has promised to parade a culprit before
journalists for raising false alarm.
</P>
<P>
The multi-national peace keeping force was sent by the
Economic Community of West African States after the civil war
broke out in Liberia seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has successfully disarmed and demobilized the warring
factions and ensured the elections which produced a new
government in the country.
</P>
<P>
The force now remains in Liberia to help keep social security
and re-build the country's armed forces and police force.
</P>
</TEXT>
