<HEADLINE> Tanzanian, Kenyan Ports Compete for Business in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Kenya sea ports
are competing in expanding their business in Uganda, The Monitor
reported today.
</P>
<P>
As the annual volume of Uganda's cargo passing the Tanzanian
port of Dar-es-Salaam had risen rapidly to 95,000 tons now from
40,000 tons two years ago, Uganda's cargo to Kenya's southern
port city Mombasa is still maintained at 1.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, Kenya Ports Authority (KPA) is
planning to open its office in Kampala, capital of Uganda, on
October 8.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Mboya, KPA's resident representative in Kampala, said
the agency also plans to organize a seminar on the facilities
offered at Mombasa port.
</P>
<P>
According to KPA, cargo transporting from Mombasa enjoys an
advantage of shorter routes and better roads with
telecommunications with Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tanzania Harbor Authority (THA) is to guarantee a
transit time of 10 days from the date of cargo arrival at the
Dar-es-Salaam port to Kampala.
</P>
<P>
A cargo usually spends at least 15 days from Mombasa to
Kampala, but Ismail Mboya promised to shorten the time of the
service.
</P>
<P>
The THA also established an office recently in Kampala.
</P>
</TEXT>
