<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Industry to Grow by 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China's rural and township
industry has entered a new stage of development after two decades
of rapid expansion and will continue to grow by an annual average
rate of 15 percent over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Liang Shusheng, an official with the Rural Industrial
Enterprises Department under the Ministry of Agriculture, offered
the prediction during a recent visit to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Liang was in Shanghai to attend an international symposium
on the comparative research of China's rural enterprises
and small to medium enterprises of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Rural industry is expected to generate 3,000 billion yuan in
gross domestic product by the year 2000, in addition to
exporting products valued at 1,000 billion yuan and providing
employment for 30 million surplus rural laborers, according to
Liang.
</P>
<P>
Rural and township enterprises, which appeared in China in the
early 1950s, have expanded at a rate of over 20 percent since 1978
when the Chinese central government introduced the reform and
opening-up policies and increased support to promote the vigorous
development of rural industry.
</P>
<P>
China now has over 23 million rural and township enterprises
with a total 135 million employees. Rural industry has become a
pillar of China's rural economy and an important component of the
country's national economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, rural industrial enterprises in China
contributed 26 percent of the nation's GDP, created 44 percent of
the total industrial output value and 35 percent of the total
earnings from exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, Myanmar Conclude Maritime Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Second Singapore-Myanmar
Joint Ministerial Working Committee (JMWC) Meeting ended here
today with the two countries concluding agreements to step up
maritime transport and trade cooperation between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement after the meeting, the two countries noted
that the Maritime Transport Agreement is the first such bilateral
agreement for Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
"It will usher in a new ear of cooperation between Singapore
and Myanmar in bilateral shipping and maritime relations as well
as in related activities such as trucking, warehousing and
container freight stations," the two countries said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the private sectors of the two countries
signed an Agreement of Cooperation between the Union of Myanmar
Chamber of Commerce and Industry (UMCCI) and the Singapore
Federation of Chamber of Commerce and Industry (SFCCI).
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the agreement will "foster greater
trade and investment ties between the two countries," and under
this agreement, "both sides will exchange market information and
provide assistance to each other's businessmen."
</P>
<P>
Lt-Gen Khin Nyunt, First Secretary of the State Law and Order
Restoration Council (SLORC) and Co-Chairman of the
Myanmar-Singapore Joint Ministerial Working Committee, said at the
end of the JMWC meeting that he believed that the agreements
signed today between the two countries will "further enhance trade
between the two countries" and will "serve as a firm foundation
for the strengthening and closer ties between Myanmar and
Singapore business communities."
</P>
<P>
Lee Yock Suan, Singapore's Minister for Trade and Industry who
co-chaired the JMWC meeting, described their discussion at the
meeting as "constructive". He said that officials of both sides
have been forthcoming with their ideas and suggestions.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, we should transform these ideas into
initiatives which can be implemented over the coming months," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Singapore signed their Economic Cooperation
Agreement in 1995 in Singapore. In the light of that agreement,
the first JMWC Meeting was held in Yangon in January 1996 to
enhance and promote economic and technical cooperation programs
between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
