<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlantis Astronauts Find Leaking Impact Points in Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Astronauts aboard U.S. space
shuttle Atlantis have visually pinpointed two impact points that
damaged the air-tightness of Russian space station Mir.
</P>
<P>
The finding, said a report from the Russian ground mission
control, was relayed back on Friday night Russian summer time
while Atlantis was hovering around Mir more than 70 meters away.
</P>
<P>
Both Atlantis and Mir were flying some 400 kilometers above the
ground then, and the crew of the space station ejected a burst of
air into the damaged and sealed-off module to help the discovery.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a shuttle astronaut and a Mir cosmonaut were able
to report seeing small particles, presumably of the protective
thermal insulation materials, floating away from the space station.
</P>
<P>
One of the two holes was later identified as near the base of a
damaged power-generating solar panel, and the other at the docking
area between the Soyuz transport craft and the space station.
</P>
<P>
The module, one of the several structures permanently attached
to Mir and designed to serve lab research purposes, was punctured
during a collision with a runaway cargo ship on June 25.
</P>
<P>
Russian experts said the finding confirmed their theory about
where the leakage areas could be.
</P>
<P>
They were also confident that Mir is safe, as Atlantis had
already supplied it, during the five-day docking with the space
station, with equipment for patching up the holes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
