<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denies Hiring Adolescents in Nuclear Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- France today denied allegation
that it had hired adolescents below 18 for jobs at its two nuclear
testing sites in the Polynesian Islands of the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The allegation was contained in a report written by two Dutch
sociologists in the Archipelago of Society in the South Pacific
and in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Out of 737 Polynesian employees of nuclear sites they
interviewed, the report said, 10 percent were below 18 and 6
percent below 16 when they worked there.
</P>
<P>
The official Direction des Centres d'Experimentations
Nucleaires (DIRCEN) of France said in a communique that it had
"never employed adolescents... or children on these sites" in
Mururoa and Fangataufa in the Polynesia.
</P>
<P>
The two investigators also said half of the employees in the
nuclear sites had not undergone medical examination on effects of
radioactivity when they left the site after completing their
contracts.
</P>
<P>
They published the report, entitled "Mururoa and Us," at the
request of a local Evangelist church in French Polynesia.
</P>
<P>
The DIRCEN said its employees have always been given medical
examinations "in conformity with the French legislation, which is
one of the most strict on the world level."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
