<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Form Agency to Deal With Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is going to set up
a national agency to tackle drug abuse in the country,
Inspector-General of Police Abdul Rahim Noor said today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is also the home minister,
will himself chair the agency whose membership will include
various relevant agencies, the police chief said.
</P>
<P>
Government agencies dealing with drug problems have always been
committed and there has never been any slackening of interest, he
told reporters after opening the Third International Private
Sector Conference on Drugs in the Workplace and the Community
(Asia Pacific Region) in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
In the case of police, he said, they now have a separate
narcotics department which indicates how serious they regard the
problem.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a lack of commitment from the people at large
toward combating drug-related problems and measures should be
taken to overcome that.
</P>
<P>
The fact that a solution has not been found for a complete cure
or an effective method to prevent relapse is a threat to the
resilience of future generations, he said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
"The Malaysian authorities are determined to make this country
a difficult hunting ground for drug traffickers and have taken the
utmost stringent steps in curbing both the demand and supply
through the enactment and enforcement of tough laws," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdul, addicts in Malaysia as a whole spend nearly
1.25 billion ringgit (about 380 million U.S. dollars) a year on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
More alarmingly, the younger generation is increasingly
affected by drug usage, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that from 1995 to August this year, more than 30,000
people have been arrested on drug charges and various drugs were
seized including 55,987 kilograms of heroin.
</P>
<P>
The conference, jointly organized by the U.N. Drug Control
Program, the International Labor Organization and the Malaysian
National Association for the Prevention of Drugs, is attended by
more than 200 participants from various governmental and
non-governmental organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
