<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks to Be Held on Teachers' Pay Dispute in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government and the
Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT) are scheduled to resume
negotiations on salary increases Monday in a bid to end teachers'
strike which entered its fourth day today.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' union was quoted by today's Kenya Times as
saying Friday that negotiations were to resume next week.
However, it maintained that the strike would continue until a
breakthrough was achieved.
</P>
<P>
KNUT Secretary General Ambrose Adongo said the meeting was
expected to discuss how to implement the new higher salary
structure as demanded by the teachers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also discuss a return-to-work formula which
must be agreeable to all parties concerned, the KNUT official
added.
</P>
<P>
As the new initiative came to light, a cross section of
Kenyans expressed support for the new dialogue efforts to end the
impending crisis.
</P>
<P>
The dispute which was taken to Industrial Court by the Kenyan
government last week has now formally been withdrawn as the
parties involved agreed on direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' union is demanding a salary increase ranging
between 150 and 200 percent for its 240,000 members while the
government has offered a salary increment of between 10 and 28
percent and an allowance increment of between 15 and 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most public schools closed with an upsurge of violent
incidents by students on Friday as the nationwide strike by
primary and secondary school teachers entered its third day on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
