<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Presses for Disaster-Coping Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-President
Brigadier-General Godfrey Miyanda has stressed the need to have
well-trained professional disaster managers and progressive
policies to combat natural and artificial calamities effectively.
</P>
<P>
Speaking here Friday at the close of a two-week international
disaster management foundation course with participants from
Zambia, Zimbabwe and Mozambique, Miyanda said advance planning,
preparation and intelligent anticipation are vital pre-requisites
for disaster management, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Since the ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) came
to power, he said, Zambia has been beset with severe droughts
which have forced the government to put in place a structure for
responding to emergencies effectively and timely.
</P>
<P>
However, the recent fires in Zambia, including the big fire
which gutted the 19-floor house of Zambia National Building
Society on September 18, are a clear indication that Zambia is
not exempted from calamities experienced in other parts of the
world, Miyanda said.
</P>
<P>
The latest disasters have exposed some aspects of disaster
management which needed to be strengthened in order to put the
country in a state of constant preparedness, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The vice president challenged participants of the course to
come up with tangible and clearly spelt-out policies to help the
government contain calamities, saying governments alone will not
make it.
</P>
<P>
The British government has pledged to support Zambia in its
efforts to combat disasters by joining relevant training programs
during the next three years, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
