<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Exports Over 3,000 Tons of Seaweed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar has exported
3,253 tons of seaweeds worth about 353 million Shillings (about
560,000 U.S. Dollars) in the last financial year, Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar government has also earned 16 million Shillings
(25,397 US Dollars) as taxes from the sale and export of the
crop, which was introduced in the country in 1990, said Deputy
Minister for Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resources Mwalimu
Haji Ameir.
</P>
<P>
Despite complaints about low price of the crop, grown on the
east coast of Pemba and Unguja islands, seaweed growers have
earned 400 million Shillings (634,921 US Dollars) from the sale
of more than 4,000 tons of the crop.
</P>
<P>
A kilogram of seaweed has gone up from 45 to 100 shillings,
Ameir said.
</P>
<P>
The crop's price would further go up after the construction of
a semi-processing seaweed plant in Zanzibar, he said, hinting
that plans were underway to look for an investor to set up the
proposed plant.
</P>
<P>
Seaweed farming is considered as the most viable economic
venture to date since the 1964 revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
