<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysian CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
During the week, CPO price on the physical market passed the
1,600 ringgit level to end at 1,680 ringgit (about 509 U.S.
dollars) per ton, 100 ringgit higher over last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Speculative covering dominated the market as the ringgit
remained soft against the U.S. dollar. The ringgit was traded
within a wide range of 3.1925/75 and 3.4550/50 throughout the week
with scattered short covering arresting any further decline. The
currency factor fueled interest in the local palm oil.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals price is expected to move higher on further
strong buying support next week, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) this week, the metal
price advanced on continuous buying support, surpassing the
20-ringgit mark to close at 20.22 ringgit per kg, an eight-year
high.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the local currency, which hovered within the 3.34
level against the greenback, attracted buyers to the KLTM.
</P>
<P>
Trading was moderately higher in the week with accumulated
turnover amounting to 476 tons against 470 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
Heavy demand was received from local, European and Japanese
buyers.
</P>
<P>
The local tin, traded in the U.S. dollar, was relatively
cheaper for buyers since the dollar's appreciation against the
local currency.
</P>
<P>
At the week's close, the KLTM's price differential to the
London Metal Exchange (LME) recorded an extremely higher premium
of 340 U.S. dollars against a premium of 20 U.S. dollars last
week.
</P>
<P>
The local metal market is likely to remain steady next week on
follow-through buying support, one trader said.
</P>
<P>
This week, the Malaysian rubber market was steady with RSS One
edging up 30 sen to 290.5 sen (about 88 U.S. cents) per kg and SMR
up 29.5 sen to 288.50 sen (about 87 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for October 2 was quoted higher at 212.23
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg this week against 197.92 cents on
September 25 last week.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 206.07 cents per kg
compared with 197.41 cents last week.
</P>
<P>
The rubber market is expected to remain steady next week, with
the next psychological level for SMR grades likely to pass the 300
sen-level on price adjustment, a market player said.
</P>
<P>
The player expected a recovery in demand from European and
local traders soon, ahead of year-end holidays.  
</P>
</TEXT>
