<HEADLINE> Uganda Lifts Ban on Cattle Semen, Embryos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
lifted the ban on importation of cattle semen and embryos, local
daily The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kezimbira Miyingo, state minister of agriculture, was quoted
as saying here on Friday that the two products will be imported
only from countries free from mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The ministry of agriculture will intensify efforts to
sensitize the public on mad cow disease, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government banned the importation of ruminants and
their products last year due to the mad cow scare which happened
in Great Britain. The ban has been maintained on the importation
of exotic cattle, but indigenous cattle from east Africa
countries are allowed inside.
</P>
<P>
In the spirit of regional cooperation, the ban on importation
of beef, beef products and animal feeds containing ruminant
material has also been maintained.
</P>
<P>
Miyingo said the meat of non-ruminant animals like pigs and
poultry will be subjected to species identification tests before
they are allowed into the country.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the government prohibited the importation of
pork sausages, fearing that it might provide a cover for people
to smuggle in beef sausages whose imports were outlawed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
