<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Suffers from Grave Shortage of Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- With water falling to the
lowest level ever in the history of Tanzania, this east African
nation is confronted with a power crisis.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the water level at the main electricity-generating
Mtera dam, which fuels the major Mtera and Kidatu power stations,
was only 0.63 meters above the minimum, latest reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It is the lowest water level ever in the history of Tanzania
and the situation is very bad," Guardian paper said in a report
today, quoting an official with the state-run Tanzania Electric
Supply Company (TANESCO).
</P>
<P>
"We are now finishing the last drops of water from the dam and
after it there will be no more water to draw electricity from,
because the turbines will automatically switch off at the minimum
level," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Low water levels have been caused by a severe drought
influenced by the El Nino weather phenomenon sweeping most of
East Africa.
</P>
<P>
Power outage -- which in some areas can last for up to 15
hours a day -- are also likely to be increased to up to four
times a week, the official said. "It's very serious and it's bad
for business."
</P>
<P>
The TANESCO official said most parts of the country would be
affected by the electricity crisis, but the impact would be
hardest in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing which may last until the arrival of short
rains normally due in November or early December, could severely
affect the economy, the paper said, adding that the slow-down of
industrial production is certain to depress income levels and
push fuel prices up.
</P>
<P>
Decrease in industrial production also means lower tax income
for the government and a lower average household income.
</P>
<P>
The electricity crisis in Tanzania also has roots in
government debts to TANESCO and in unpaid bills -- mostly from
parastatal institutions -- of some 14 billion Tanzania shillings,
or more than 20 million U.S. dollars, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
This debt has made TANESCO unable to buy fuel and spare parts
for diesel generators supposed to be used amid severe water
shortages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
