<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> How A Chinese Village Gets Rich (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The village head of Dongdian in
the southern outskirts of Beijing neither looks nor behaves like
an old-fashioned stereotype: a bare-footed peasant cadre wearing a
straw hat and talking about the fulfillment of quotas.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Zhao Jinfu wears leather-shoes, an all-cotton golf
shirt and discusses market prices from a mobile phone in an
air-conditioned office. On his name card he is titled "General
Manager".
</P>
<P>
This professional image has an approach to match if the
village's economy is anything to go by. Located in Daxing County,
less than an hour's drive from Beijing, Dongdian is a booming
village-corporation, calling itself rather long-windedly the Da
Dong Agricultural, Industrial and Commercial United Company. Zhao
is in charge of it.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it produced farm and industrial products worth 75
million yuan (nine million US dollars). Its operations include a
150-ha farm yielding wheat, corn, fruit and vegetables, a
10,000-head pig farm plus a slaughterhouse, a chicken farm, a feed
factory and an instant-noodle factory.
</P>
<P>
Besides contributing substantially to Beijing's larders,
Dongdian also has an artificial diamond plant, an auto parts
factory and a dozen other businesses.
</P>
<P>
Not only has Zhao become rich, the villagers have also. In
1996, the average per-capita income was 6,500 yuan, doubling the
average earnings of other farmers elsewhere in the Beijing
Municipality.
</P>
<P>
"We still consider ourselves' an agricultural economy, but a
modern one," said Zhao Jinfu. "Our entire business is structured
on the basis of farm production, but at the same time we have
complementary processing industries for added value -- basically
we cater to the market."
</P>
<P>
What's happening in Dongdian is termed "Chan Ye Hua", or
industrialization of farm production, a new trend found in some of
China's most prosperous rural areas, particularly the east and
south.
</P>
<P>
Farmers here have moved away from just growing, harvesting and
selling. To maximize their profits, they are mass-producing farm
products, processing them and setting up wholesale firms to
channel their value-added products to markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> How A Chinese Village Gets Rich (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In all Beijing's six suburban counties, "chan ye hua" is
developing quickly with support from local governments. In Shunyi
County, northeast of the city, for instance, the local government
has invested some 40 billion yuan over the last five years to
improve land quality, build irrigation facilities and lay power
cables to villages.
</P>
<P>
Shunyi is now Beijing's vegetable basket, a huge green-house
county with two processing plants. It sold more than 800 million
kg of vegetables to Beijing in 1996, earning 529 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Dongdian's core products are grains, vegetables and meat. Its
fields are beautifully vast, with two-meter high corn stalks
reaching for the sky in mid-summer. But strangely, all is
quiet. There's nobody in sight.
</P>
<P>
Mechanization has taken the backache and blisters out of
farming, leaving many more villagers to concentrate on farm
management and factory work.
</P>
<P>
More than 850 locals once worked in the fields. today, only
eight people take care of them. In 1996, the village harvested
more than 900 tons of wheat and corn, and one million kg of
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
This year, farmers are trying something new: they bought seeds
from a nearby space science institute which had been flown in
space and brought back by recoverable satellite. They harvested
green peppers, tomatoes and cucumbers which were indeed out of
this world -- huge, juicy, sweet. And they sold for suitably
astronomical prices.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are always looking for ways to add value to their
harvest. "It is true that farm production is the basis of our
livelihood, but without industry, we can't really get rich, and
without the market, we can't get the money," village
head-cum-general manager Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, factories have been built. They now contribute more
than 60 percent to the wealth of the village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> How A Chinese Village Gets Rich (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New operations have created jobs, employing those hands made
idle by tractors, planters, sprayers and harvesters. Today more
than 300 villagers work in factories and two trading companies.
</P>
<P>
Sun Shuhui, a 40-year-old peasant woman, is one of them. She
has a full-time job as a warehouse keeper in the village's animal
and poultry feed factory. She works eight hours a day, five days a
week, enjoying a full weekends' rest just as urban residents do.
</P>
<P>
"But I help out in the fields for two weeks or so over the busy
harvest seasons," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Chan ye hua" requires Dongdian Village to pool its natural and
human resources together under collective management. The
villagers seem to be proud of this.
</P>
<P>
"It is more efficient and economical and allows us to achieve
an optimum-scale farming," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government welcomes this method, but would like to
see it being propagated in a gradual process. Considering that
most parts of China's countryside are still economically
undeveloped, the government says a household-based farming system
still props up the country's agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In a recent speech, China's Minister of Agriculture Liu Jiang
said that this system will probably continue for at least another
30 years.
</P>
<P>
He also conceded that fact that "chan ye hua" is here to stay
and is farming's future niche in the market economy currently
under assembly in China. The government should "guide" farmers, he
said, to pursue farming on a rationally large scale and establish
processing industries of farm produce in places suited to the
system.
</P>
<P>
With Beijing as its market, Dongdian village is clearly such a
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Submits Truce Rules to Muslim Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators from the
government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebel
group today ended their eighth round of low-level talks in
Cotabato City, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the government panel submitted its version of
the ground rules for a general cease-fire in the southern
Philippines. The rebel group had rendered its version earlier.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs,
failed to give specifics. But he said that among the conditions
raised by the government are that no MILF flags will be hoisted
in tolerated areas, no future rebel training conducted and no
sanctuary or assistance provided to lawless elements. MILF
elements are also asked to refrain from committing hostile and
provocative actions against government forces.
</P>
<P>
To give time for the MILF to study the government's truce
scheme, Jaafar said both panels have decided to meet again on
November 12 and 13 with the agenda still focusing on the general
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jaafar said the MILF is pushing for an assessment of
the redelopyment or withdrawal of government troops in Rajah Muda,
Pikit and other areas in Cotabato Province as the two sides had
agreed earlier.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member separatist group of the mainstream
rebel group, the Moro National Liberation Front, which signed a
peace agreement with the government last year.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, the MILF has begun a series of peace
talks with the government, but made little progress toward forging
a peace deal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
