MOSCOW -- A seasoned Russian astronaut has expressed optimism
over the fate of Russian Mir space station, saying that as long as
Mir's equipment is regularly replaced with new spare parts, it
will continue to work for many more years.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Titov, who was on board the space shuttle Atlantis,
said that Mir is currently functioning well, though it is aging as
human beings are.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Atlantis brought Mir a new central computer which
was installed and then programmed with the information needed to
keep the station on a correct orientation. (Russia-Astronaut-Mir)
