<HEADLINE> Hu Gangjun Regains Title in Beijing Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Hu Gangjun of China won the
title of the 17th Beijing International Marathon in a time of 2
hours 9 minutes and 18 seconds here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The winning time also gave Hu the gold medal of China's Eighth
National Games as well.
</P>
<P>
Hu also registered China's best result in marathon race to
take the 10,000 U.S. dollars prize.
</P>
<P>
Hu, 26, was followed by Hao Lijun, also from Inner Mongolia, at
the second place at 2:13:25. Defending champion Nelson Ndereva of
Kenya finished third with 5 seonds behind.
</P>
<P>
Hu, who won the race in 1993 and 1994 but finished runner-up in
1995 and 1996, broke away from the leading pack at the 12
kilometers mark and was never challenged after that.
</P>
<P>
"I should have run faster if the pool was more competitive,"
said Hu, who became the first Chinese to break the 2 hours 10
minutes barrier. "The weather was fine, but it's a little bit
windy."
</P>
<P>
In the women's race, China's Pan Jinhong clinched the title
with a personal best of 2 hours, 26 minutes and 39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
She was followed by compatriots Wang Jianfen at 2:26:58 and Ai
Dongmei at 2:27:30.
</P>
<P>
Pan, the bronze medalist in last year's race, was not in the
leading group in the first 10 kilometers. But she surged ahead in
the last six kilometers and improved her personal best by more
than 3 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
