<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) market closed the week mixed under
pressure over the weakening of the local currency, the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian currency touched its all-time low and traded in a
wide range of 3.1925/75 and 3.4550/50 against the U.S. dollar
throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
The 100-stock Composite Index fell 2.52 points to close the
week at 797.29, the all Main Board share Emas Index 1.93 points at
224.89 and the Second Board Index 3.54 points to 401.05. But
against the trend, the Industrial Index edged up 9.49 points to
1,640.99.
</P>
<P>
During the week, there were two new listings on the KLSE's
Second Board. Sarawak-based Yung Kong Galvanising, which had its
first trade done at 5 ringgit for a premium of 1.5 ringgit over an
offer price of 3.5 ringgit and manufacturer of firefighting
systems, the CME Group, also opened at 5 ringgit over its offer
price of 3.5 ringgit for a 1.5 ringgit premium.
</P>
<P>
The 10 top active shares included Renong, Sime Darby, Anson
Perdana, Tenaga Nasional, Kim Hin, Timberwell, Metro Kajang,
Commerce-Asset, Mancon and North Borneo Timber and most of them
were down.
</P>
<P>
The weekly Main Board ready turnover dwindled to 761.785
million valued at 3.669 billion ringgit (about 1.111 billion U.S.
dollars) from 937.798 million shares worth 4.089 billion ringgit
(about 1.239 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 44.245
million shares traded, industrial products 99.749 million shares,
construction 96.18 million shares, trading/services 159.028
million shares, infrastructure 6.621 million shares, finance
121.935 million shares, hotels 2.782 million shares, properties
110.424 million shares, plantation 66.366 million shares, mining
4.71 million shares, trusts 962,000 shares, close-end fund 545,000
shares, loan stocks 13.14 million shares, TSR/warrants 32.769
million shares and rights 2.32 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The Second Board turnover was 129.647 million shares valued at
1.105 billion ringgit (about 334.848 million dollars) from 120.926
million shares worth 968.958 million ringgit (about 293.623
million dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals amounted to 104.583 million valued at 1.12
billion ringgit (about 339.393 million dollars) from 109.973
million shares worth 818.652 million ringgit (about 248.076
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
