<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Agriculture: Feeding 1.2 Billion People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by the
Chinese Ministry of Agriculture show that in 1949 China, with a
population of just 400 million, produced food grains weighing
113.2 million tons, or 283 kg per capita, while in 1996, the
average per capita production was 400 kg.
</P>
<P>
In particular, they say, food production has rocketed since
1995, recording consecutive increases of 4.8 and five percent. The
latter figure, they predict, will be bettered this year.
</P>
<P>
But the proof of the pudding is in the eating: what is the
situation in food markets across the country?
</P>
<P>
Taking food supply in Beijing, the capital of China, as a
measure of agricultural production would be a little
misleading. Capitals do tend to have the best of
everything. Indeed, off Beijing's main avenues there are markets
in every neighborhood, each one a parking area for
tricycle-trailers.
</P>
<P>
They are piled high with fruit, vegetables, grains, fish, meat,
poultry and eggs.
</P>
<P>
The supply at just one such local market would easily outweigh
an entire town's supply of the same produce in Europe or North
America, where people eat more processed and fewer fresh and dried
foods.
</P>
<P>
Provincial larders too seem equally oversupplied. That's good
for shoppers: they can bargain. And in the countryside there
actually seems more food than farmers can deal with.
</P>
<P>
They spread out their produce along the road: grains are
drying; baskets of apples, peaches and plums wait for
transportation. Grain silos are full. China seems to be bulging at
its seams with food.
</P>
<P>
It's a far cry from the days of rationing and queuing of just
15 years ago. The early 80s in turn were brighter than the dark
days of the 60s and early 70s when ideology harnessed the plow.
</P>
<P>
Peasants were bogged down studying political directives and
attending collective meetings. Nowadays, Chinese farmers are more
likely to be reading pamphlets on crop rotation, pesticide
application or drip irrigation techniques. Meetings have become
courses at which experts teach the nitty gritty of the latest
agrotechnology. Directives do still come from the government, but
they are practical, not political.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Agriculture: Feeding 1.2 Billion People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Things started to change in 1979, with the advent of reforms,
which actually started in the countryside in the form of the
household contract responsibility system. Peasant families
contracted use of land. They were no longer obliged to turn all
their produce over to the state. Instead, once they had fulfilled
their quota, they were free to sell off any surplus, or grow cash
crops.
</P>
<P>
During the 80s, farming required less brawn and more
brains. New techniques have boosted yields. Under the
responsibility system and by adopting scientific techniques, grain
production averaged an annual two percent increase between 1979
and 1994.
</P>
<P>
China will hit its agricultural goal set for the year 2000
three years early if it can harvest 500 million tons of food grain
this year. Barring major natural disasters, the ministry is
certain that the target will be broken, making 1997 the third
bumper year in succession.
</P>
<P>
The future augurs equally well concerning policy, unswerving
not swinging. Liu Jiang, minister of agriculture, has said that
the family-based farming system will remain and be improved upon
over the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Despite the string of bumper harvests, the government is not
resting on any laurels. It continually reiterates the paramount
importance of agriculture at national, provincial and even
municipal levels. National purchasing price on food grain has been
lifted for years to make planting food crops a more profitable
business.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China is on the offensive, making dry lands
productive by the construction of irrigation facilities and with
measures to halt the spread of deserts.
</P>
<P>
More stunning is the fact that China feeds itself, 22 percent
of the planet's population, to previously unknown levels of
contentedness by farming on just seven percent of the world's
arable land. Hunger is now history for all but a minute fraction
of Chinese, with cries about a hungry China drowned by the roar of
combine harvesters reaping record yields in all of the nation's
breadbaskets.
</P>
<P>
The call for a good harvest will be answered, but it's outcome
rests no longer entirely in the hands of the gods. While they do
unleash the occasional flood or hailstorm, China's food production
is, in the main, dependent on sound policies, market incentives,
science and technology. All that's really needed from nature is
the sun and rain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
