<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Central, Eastern Europe Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The direct foreign investment in
Central and Eastern European countries has dropped from 14 billion
U.S. dollars in 1995 to 12 billion dollars in 1996, according to a
local report.
</P>
<P>
Hungary and the Czech Republic, which are two of the main
receivers of foreign investment in the region, have witnessed a
fall in foreign investment from 4.6 billion dollars and 2.6
billion dollars in 1995 to 2 billion and 1.2 billion dollars
respectively, said the newspaper "International Market" in an
article based on data released by the United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development.
</P>
<P>
The drop was attributed to the decrease of investment from West
Europe and the United States in the privatization programs of
those countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said the investment in Poland, which is
also a major regional money absorber, has increased from 3.7
billion dollars in 1995 to a record 5.2 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the service industry and improvement of
competition mechanism in economy are the main reasons for the
rise, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
