<HEADLINE> Russian Astronaut Expresses Optimism Over Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A seasoned Russian astronaut has
expressed optimism over the fate of Russian Mir space station,
saying that as long as Mir's equipment is regularly replaced with
new spare parts, it will continue to work for many more years.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Titov, who was on board the space shuttle Atlantis,
said that Mir is currently functioning well, though it is aging as
human beings are.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Atlantis brought Mir a new central computer which
was installed and then programmed with the information needed to
keep the station on a correct orientation.
</P>
<P>
Mir has suffered a serious of mishaps recently, including
repeated computer breakdowns, power outages and a severe crash
with a cargo craft in June.
</P>
<P>
But Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin reassured
earlier this week that adequate measures have been taken to ensure
the safety of the astronauts on Mir.
</P>
<P>
The 11-year-old station, which has a designed operational life
of only five years, was launched in 1986 and had overworked in the
space for six years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
