<HEADLINE> Thai Rice Exports to Philippines Under Negotiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand plans to sell 100,000
tons of white rice to the Philippines under a
government-to-government contract aimed at boosting rice exports,
according to the Thai Commerce Ministry's Foreign Trade
Department.
</P>
<P>
The price is still under negotiation, but the deal is expected
to be finalized next week, Pracha Jarutrakulchai, director-general
of the department, was quoted today by the local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the Philippines wants to import 3.5 million tons of
rice this year and Thailand is among rice exporting countries
including China and Vietnam seeking to fulfill the order.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand's rice export performance is expected to
recover next year as many export rivals, including Vietnam, India
and Myanmar, have suffered severe flooding, resulting in lower
rice production.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, countries such as Indonesia and the Philippines will
need to import more rice for domestic consumption next year as the
El Nino effect has affected their rice yields.
</P>
<P>
Pracha said both Indonesia and the Philippines are expected to
buy more rice from Thailand. "We are not being seriously impacted
by the El Nino situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand plans to submit 70,000 tons of rice for export
to Japan, and another 20,000 tons and 40,000 tons respectively to
South Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. The
sales will improve the rice export performance this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
