<HEADLINE> Weak Baht Spurs Thai Chicken Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai chicken exports are
expected to reach 190,000 tons this year, compared with 145,000
tons last year, according to the Poultry Promotion Association of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's export volume increased by 16 to 17 percent to
70,000 tons in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Lower prices causing by the baht's devaluation have importers
worldwide shift their orders to Thailand, Sa-nguan Jantaranukul,
president of the association was quoted today by the local press
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the value of chicken exports are forecast to reach 17
billion baht to 18 billion baht (485 million to 514 million U.S.
dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the baht's depreciation also helped narrow the gap in
production costs between Thailand and China to 10 percent from 30
percent, making Thailand's exports more attractive.
</P>
<P>
Sa-nguan said China's export competitiveness has fallen because
of higher production costs resulting from technological
developments and raw material imports.
</P>
<P>
Japan is still the main export market of Thai chicken,
accounting for 80 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
