<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Sector Achieves Rapid Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China's post and
telecommunications industry kept its rapid and steady growth in
the first eight months this year, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The sector registered a total 111.01 billion yuan (about 13.37
billion US dollars) in traffic turnover during the period, an
increase of 33 percent over the same period last year, according
to sources with the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications (MPT).
</P>
<P>
It earned a total of 108.87 billion yuan in business revenues,
a rise of 37.7 percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging news comes amid growing pressure imposed upon
the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications in recent months, with
many government officials and experts urging the opening up of
China's telecommunications sector, which has been an MPT monopoly
for decades.
</P>
<P>
President and Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin said in his
15th National Party Congress report that industrial monopolies
should be gradually phased out.
</P>
<P>
According to MPT sources, China's mobile telephone subscribers
totaled 10.93 million by the end of August, a dramatic jump from
the 10 million recorded in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
China has the world's third largest mobile phone network, after
the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992-96 period, the country's total number of mobile
phone subscribers expanded at an average annual rate of 170
percent.
</P>
<P>
The country has an average urban telephone coverage rate of 25
percent at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
Its total telephone switching capacity had reached 100 million
lines by that time, the second largest telephone network in the
world, and not very far behind the United States, according to the
the Post and Telecommunications Minister Wu Jichuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
