<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Seeks Close Cooperation With International Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev said here today that Kazakhstan hopes to boost
cooperation with international organizations in all fields,
especially in economy.
</P>
<P>
Enhancing cooperation with international bodies will be
beneficial to Kazakhstan's economic integration with the
international community, said Nazarbayev while meeting Iva
Bertelo, executive secretary of the U.N. Economic Commission for
Europe (ECE), and Adrianus Mooy, executive secretary of the U.N.
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh president also voiced his support for an
international exhibition of the Asia-Pacific region to be held in
Alma Ata in October 1998, saying that the exhibition mainly on
daily consumer goods and food industry will help promote
Kazakhstan's global economic integration.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Bertelo told a press conference that the
United Nations had spoken highly of Nazarbayev's initiative to
establish the SPEKA -- a U.N. development commission for
Central-Asian independent countries. He said the initiative will
score the United Nations' support and the International Monetary
Fund's assistance.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the ECE and ESCAP, together with experts from
Kazakhstan, formulated a SPEKA development program a year after
Kazakhstan's president proposed the establishment of the SPEKA at
the U.N. Assembly in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
The four-year program, which consists of 32 projects in
technical assistance in infrastructure, industrial transformation,
energy, foreign investment and protection of trade and environment
and other fields, will be implemented beginning 1998. 
</P>
