<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Central Bank Tries to Support Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, has introduced a new foreign exchange trading facility for
export-oriented companies in its latest move to shore up the
falling rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The facility includes arrangements for swaps and forward
purchases for the country's 580 registered exporters, Bank
Indonesia Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono said when announcing the
new policy here Friday, Antara News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The swap facility is aimed at encouraging these exporters to
unload their dollar holdings," Soedradjad said.
</P>
<P>
The new swap facility allows export companies to buy dollars
through forward transactions with 11 foreign exchange banks
appointed by Bank Indonesia. These appointed banks can then
continue the transactions with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the export-oriented companies can also sell
their foreign exchange earnings through forward transactions with
Bank Indonesia. Previously such transactions could be carried out
only outside the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor did not say how effective the new
move would be in stabilizing the local currency, but he noted that
the new facility would protect exporters from the sharp
fluctuation of the rupiah against the dollar and ensure that they
would get the dollar they need from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia issued early last month a ruling limiting
forward foreign exchange trading by domestic banks to non-resident
customers to 5 million dollars in a bid to confine speculative
dollar buying.
</P>
<P>
But the move was unsuccessful as the rush for dollars continued,
with the rupiah further losing ground.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah plunged to a new historic low of 3,725 against the
dollar in mid-day trading Friday before recovering to 3,395/3,405
at close. It has lost about 50 percent of its value against the
American greenback since January this year.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad said this week's plunge was partly due to a sharp
increase in demand for the dollar from local companies either to
finance their offshore debts or imports.
</P>
<P>
However, economists here said the dramatic fall by the rupiah
showed the country's economy was going through its toughest time
since the oil crisis in the 1980s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
