<HEADLINE> 300,000 Thais Expected to Lose Jobs by Year-End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- About 300,000 people in Thailand
may lose their jobs by the end of this year, the Thailand
Development Research Institute has predicted.
</P>
<P>
A large number of cash-strapped companies and factories have
closed or reduced their operations at a time of economic slowdown,
and others are expected to follow suit during the last three
months of the year, leading to mass lay-offs, according to the
Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
The layoffs will include not only blue-collar workers, but also
white-collar workers, graduates from secondary and tertiary
educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
Yongyuth Chalaemwong, director of Labor Research of the
institute, urged relevant government agencies to take the issue
seriously and provide workers with training to improve their
skills.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the government to encourage foreign investment so
as to create more job opportunities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
