<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Breaks 3,700 Mark Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah broke the
3,700 barrier against the U.S. dollar Friday, a fall of 8 percent,
as the rush for the American currency continued on the local
foreign currency market, dealers here said today.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah plunged to a new historic low of 3,725 against the
dollar in mid-day trading, but it managed to recover in the
afternoon to close at 3,640/50, a 7-percent drop from its
3,395/3,405 opening.
</P>
<P>
The dealers attributed the drop of the rupiah's value to a
continued increase in the demand for dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the rupiah's dramatic fall Friday showed that
the country's economy was going through its toughest time since
the oil crisis in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad Djiwandono, governor of Bank Indonesia, the
country's central bank, said earlier that many companies bought
dollars to pay their dollar-denominated debts.
</P>
<P>
According to data from a business consulting firm, the Castle
Group, Indonesian private offshore debt reached 55.52 billion
dollars last year, of which about 34.24 billion dollars would
mature in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad said Friday that the central bank would intervene in
the market if conditions allowed.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah's value has declined by more than 50 percent against
the dollar since the beginning of the year, especially since early
July when the rupiah came under speculative attack.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index lost
about 4 percent to close at 515.47 points.
</P>
<P>
Securities analysts and brokers blamed the plunge of share
prices on the weakening rupiah in the currency market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
