<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Attorney General Moves on with Gore Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno said she has begun a preliminary investigation into White
House fund-raising phone calls made by Vice President Gore, a
process that could lead to an independent counsel probe.
</P>
<P>
Reno told the three-judge panel that because she has been
unable to determine "whether there is sufficient specific and
credible evidence to suggest a violation of federal law," she must
begin the probe under the provisions of the independent counsel
law.
</P>
<P>
In a court document filed with the panel Friday, the attorney
general cites the brevity of a 30-day review of Gore's phone calls
and "the complexity of the factual and legal issues presented by
this matter."
</P>
<P>
At the end of what will be a 60-day investigation, she must
either ask for an extension, drop the probe for lack of evidence
or ask the panel to appoint an independent counsel to investigate
the case.
</P>
<P>
Gore made between 40 and 50 calls from the White House in 1995
and 1996 to raise fund before the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
A 1883 federal law bans the solicitation of campaign funds on
federal property, but the law has only been used when the person
being asked for money was on federal property.
</P>
<P>
It has never been used to prosecute someone on federal property
making a phone call to a potential contributor elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Private Funds for Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government plans
to modify its successful build-operate-transfer (BOT) scheme to
attract private funds for infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Trade and Industry Undersecretary Ernesto
Ordonez, who also chairs the Presidential Committee for Flagship
Projects, the newspaper The Philippine Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Since an entire project may not be financially attractive to
the private sector, the government will have to divide the project
to interested private investors and with a portion of it to be
funded by the government, Ordonez told a press conference on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
This way, major infrastructure projects which would require
massive investments will be assured of funding and thus will be
implemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ordonez added that President Fidel Ramos has agreed to take on
the innovative approach on the BOT scheme.
</P>
<P>
The BOT program has been proven an effective way to attract
both local and foreign investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, investors build their businesses with tax
break and other incentives provided by the government. After
several years of operation, they transfer the ownership of the
enterprises to the Philippine government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
