<HEADLINE> Pudong International Airport Gets Japanese Government Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Pudong International
Airport received 40 billion yen (about 327 million US dollars) in
Japanese government loans from the Export and Import Bank of China
(Eximbank), according to a report in Business Weekly of China
Daily today.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest yen loan for airport construction in China.
</P>
<P>
The loan, part of the fourth group of Japanese government loans
that started in 1996, has a 2.3 percent interest rate, a 30-year
term and a 10-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The loan is the last of foreign funds designed for the airport,
which will be one of the three biggest air traffic centers in
China.
</P>
<P>
The airport, due for completion at the end of 1999, is designed
to handle 20 million people and 500,000 tons of cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
It will help Shanghai become an international economic,
financial and trade center and boost economic growth of the
Shanghai and Yangtze River regions.
</P>
<P>
As the bank authorized by the Chinese Government to handle
foreign government loans, China Eximbank, a policy bank, handles
loans from 14 countries and regions, such as Japan, Kuwait,
Germany, Belgium and Australia. 
</P>
