<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truancy in US Relates to Rising Juvenile Crime Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 3 (Xinhua) -- An interactive voice
response system has been installed in six public high schools in
Oakland, central California of the United States, as an effort to
curb rampant truancy.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday evening, the first day when the School Calling
System was operational, 2,500 parents received automated calls at
home and were told that their children were not in school.
</P>
<P>
The computerized message, personalized with the truant
student's school and grade level but not the student name, is
offered in Chinese, Cambodian, English, Laotian, Spanish and
Vietnamese. Parents are given the opportunity to excuse their
child absence by phone, using a confidential personal
identification number. Parents or guardians are required to obtain
their personal identification numbers by signing up in person at
the child's school.
</P>
<P>
In addition to being notified when kids are absent, parents are
also able to call in and get a child's attendance records for the
past 20 days. The Oakland Unified School District plans to expand
the phone system by giving parents and guardians the latest
school news as well as a teacher hot line offering specific
message about home work assignments, test schedule and class
projects.
</P>
<P>
Of 53,000 students enrolled in the district in the 1995-96
school year, 18 percent were habitually truant who had at least
six unexcused absences.
</P>
<P>
Oakland's efforts to abate truance is aided by local law
enforcement. Habitually truant students can be subject to
prosecution in Oakland. The juvenile court has the authority to
order them to perform 40 hours of community service, pay a fine of
100 dollars and suspend a student driver's license or eligibility
to apply for one.
</P>
<P>
What Oakland is doing is part of nationwide efforts to find new
ways to keep young people in school and avoid drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
Truancy is the "red blinking light that tells us that a young
person may be going down the wrong road," said Secretary of
Education Richard Riley, acknowledging that the fact that while
the nation's crime rate is going down, the juvenile crime rate is
continuing to go up.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Department of Education announced a 10 million
dollar discretionary grant program to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1996 manual to combat truancy worked out by the
department in cooperation with the Department of Justice, while no
national data on the extent of truancy exists, in some cities
unexcused absences can number in the thousands each day.
</P>
<P>
The manual cited Pittsburgh, where each day approximately 3,500
students or 12 percent of the pupil population are absent and 7
percent of those absences are unexcused. In Philadelphia, 2,500
students a day are absent with an excuse. And in Milwaukee, on any
given school day there are 4,000 unexpected absences.
</P>
<P>
"Truancy is a gateway to crime," said the manual, which had
been sent to every schoold district in the nation. "High rates of
truancy are linked to high daytime burglary and high vandalism."
</P>
<P>
During a sample period in Miami, for instance, more than 71
percent of 13 to 16 year-olds prosecuted for criminal violations
had been truants.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to offer parents, school officials, law enforcement
agencies and communities a set of principles to design their own
strategies to combat truancy, the manual stressed that parents
play the fundamental role in the education of the children and
that school districts should communicate to their students that
they have zero tolerance for truancy.
</P>
<P>
Several states in the United States have daytime curfews during
school hours that allow law enforcement officers to question youth
to determine if their absence is legitimate.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department also urged schools to develop
initiatives to combat the root cause of truancy, including
turoring programs, added security measures, drug prevention and
mentorship through community and religious groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
