<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 00:30 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Shuttle Atlantis separated from the Russian
space station Mir Friday after six days of linked flight during
which the Mir was replenished with a new central computer and a
fresh American astronaut, the NASA's Space Center in Houston said.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle slowly pulled away from Mir at 1:28 p.m. EDT (17:28
GMT) as the spacecraft soared 250 miles (420 km) above
southeastern Russia, leaving David Wolf behind for a four-month
stay. His American predecessor, Michael Foale, was aboard Atlantis
to back Earth after a stressful four and a half month mission on
the Mir.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis arrived last weekend and brought for the Mir a new
central computer, spare batteries and repair equipment it needs
because of a collision with a cargo ship in
June. (US-Shuttle-Mir-Separation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
