<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Mark, Rises Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar approached a
five-month high against the yen today, lifted by a jump in oil
prices after the situation in the Persian Gulf got intensified.
</P>
<P>
Japan's dependency on imported oil makes its economy vulnerable
to any supply interruptions. More investors believed that Japan
would sell yen for the dollar to buy more expensive oil.
</P>
<P>
The dollar lost ground against the German mark on stable U.S.
jobs figures that suggested Germany will be raising interest rates
before the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
In late trading in New York, the dollar was quoted at 122.03
Japanese yen, up from 121.65 late Thursday. The dollar bought
1.7572 German marks, down from 1.7725.
</P>
<P>
Oil on the New York Mercantile Exchange rose 99 cents to its
highest level since February.
</P>
<P>
Germany's central bankers have said a lot in recent weeks to
cause expectations of an interest rate hike there, making the mark
and mark-denominated securities more attractive.
</P>
<P>
In other markets, the British pound was quoted at 1.6155 U.S.
dollars, down from 1.6160 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.4475 Swiss francs, down from 1.4557; 1,722.00 lire, up
from 1,739.50; and 1.3725 Canadian dollars, down from 1.3728.
</P>
