<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece said today that it would
choose "the right place, method and time of responding to the
report claiming the existence of Kurdish terrorist training camps
in Greece, which appeared in the British newspaper The Observer
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said that the Greek government was examining all
possibilities including legal action over the "libellous" report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Greek Foreign Ministry said tonight in a
statement that it would examine the effect on the country's good
reputation of the report, which Greece had immediately rejected
and described as "totally unfounded."
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the Observer report, based on the claims
of some Kurd (Seydo Hazar) who lived in Germany until the
beginning of the year, was of course "beyond the ethics of
journalism," and it was deplorable that a serious British
newspaper was drawn into it, adopting "a classic provocation."
</P>
<P>
"Of the fabrications which comprise it nothing is new, some of
these inaccuracies have already appeared since 1991, and have, at
various times, been promoted by circles wishing to increase the
tension in Greek-Turkish relations," the ministry said. 
</P>
