<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Seesaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 3 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks seesawed today,
first rallying on a positive jobs report, then retreating on
concerns over tensions in the Middle East, before bouncing back by
the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 11.05 at 8,038.58. The
index rose as much as 116.89 points in early trading, and then
slipped over 71 points by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 619.42 million
shares as against 472.71 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indexes also closed higher today, extending
Thursday's record-breaking gains.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.57 to 965.03, and
the NYSE composite index rose 2.26 to 505.69.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 13.45 to 1,715.86, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.96 to 709.92,
setting a new record.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rallied this morning, following bonds higher after the
Labor Department reported the unemployment rate was unchanged at
4.9 percent in September, remaining near a 24-year low.
</P>
<P>
Bond prices immediately shot higher after the jobs report was
released, sending the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to a
20-month low of 6.16 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the early gains in stocks and bonds were mostly erased by
mid-afternoon on concerns that turmoil in the Middle East could
disrupt oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices shot up about 1.20 U.S. dollars per barrel
higher on the New York Mercantile Exchanges on reports of
tension in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
By late afternoon, the Treasury yield was down to 6.28 percent,
slightly lower than 6.29 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
