<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saint Lucia Calls for WTO Procedure Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- There must be fundamental
reform to the system of dispute settledment if the World Trade
Organization (WTO) was to be of any value to developing countries,
Dr. Kenny D. Anthony, prime minister of Saint Lucia, stressed here
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the General Assembly, the prime
minister said the small banana producing countries of the
Caribbean Community last month received a particularly harsh and
crushing blow, when the Apples Board of the WTO upheld an earlier
finding that the preferential treatment accorded in the European
market to bananas of the African, Caribbean and Pacific countries
contravened WTO rules on free trade.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the reform to the WTO was essential
because the implications of the scope of the ruling on bananas
were not confined to bananas only. The ruling raised the question
about other import agreements for agricultural goods as well as
the future of trade and development of cooperation agreements
between the rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Anthony said that the real challenge to the WTO was not how
effective its Dispute Settlement Body could be in rigidly applying
the letter of its regulations, but rather whether the process by
which decisions were arrived was perceived as being fair.
</P>
<P>
He said the system must be reformed so that it took account of
the consequences of the implementation of its ruling. It must of
necessity consider the impact of its decisions, particularly in
the case of the ruling of the banana regime, the affected
countries had small, vulnerable and fragile economies.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the WTO would establish a standard of arbitration
premised on fairness, civilized negotiation of vital interests and
the calculation of equity in international trade and commerce.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added trade and development must be about
the development of people and the WTO criteria for settling
disputes must be redesigned to take account of social, health,
cultural and environmental issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Airports Gear Up for Cargo Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Los Angeles International
Airport, the world's busiest, is undergoing a 12 billion dollar
expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
By 2015, when the plan is completed, the airport will increase
passengers by 60 percent, from last year's 58 million to 93
million. Meanwhile, it will handle 420 million tons of air cargo,
as compared with 172 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 cargo flights depart and arrive in the world's
largest airport every day, nearly 80 percent of which are shipping
commodities between U.S. and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles International Airport expansion is but part of a
trend in the U.S., where airports are improving their facilities
as a growing number of industries rely more and more on the rapid
movement of their products from factory to market by air.
</P>
<P>
Walter Johnson, ex-president of the Miami-based International
Air Cargo Association, said in a recent interview that air cargo
currently moves approximately 36 percent to 40 percent of the
world's trade. This drives airports around the world, particularly
in the U.S., to supply new facilities to decrease so-called ground
delay issues that inhibit the movement of goods by air.
</P>
<P>
Miami International Airport, the second busiest airport in the
world handling 171 million tons of air cargo last year, is putting
into effect a smaller plan to improve capacities for flights
between the U.S. and Latin American states. The implementation of
the 10-year-old plan needs 4 billion dollars and increases its air
cargo by 134 percent in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of facilities in Denver International Airport
is aiming to accelerate trade and economic cooperation from Canada
in the north through the U.S. Midwest to Mexico in the south. The
so-called "city-sized airport," occupying a land of 53 square
miles, will complete in eight to 10 years and become the center of
air cargo flights for the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Any improvement in air cargo capability into the next century
"must include airports and, above all, include government, which
today plays a major role in establishing the benchmarks of
process," Johnson said, adding that for individual air carriers,
air cargo operations are the key to their survival.
</P>
<P>
According to data released by the International Air Transport
Association, cargo operations account for as much as 20 percent of
an air carrier's annual revenues, and even as much as 35 percent
in the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
