<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Financial Situation Continues to Be Difficult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N.
Under-Secretary-General for Management Joseph Conner today
described the world body as resting "on a precarious financial
perch."
</P>
<P>
He told the Fifth Commission (Administrative and Budgetary) of
the General Assembly that there are high arrearage levels,
deficits in regular budget cash, prolonged borrowings from
peace-keeping budgets and continuing inability to liquidate debt
to member states for peace-keeping troops and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Unpaid dues amounted to 2.417 billion U.S. dollars at the end
of September 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unpaid dues exceed current year dues by a ratio of 1.07 to 1,
the highest since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The ratio stood at 0.79 in 1995 and 0.61 in 1992, he said,
adding that "the warning flag is waving now."
</P>
<P>
"The major contributor," referring to the United States,
accounts for 60 percent of all amounts owed to the organization,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the U.N. has been on a deficit position, with
deficits periods of four or so months as usual, he said.
</P>
<P>
A negative balance cash position of 261 million dollars is
forecast for the end of 1997 and the negative situation will
persist for five months in 1998, Cannor said.
</P>
<P>
"We estimate that at year end we will owe 907 million dollars
to troop and equipment contributing countries up from 838 million
dollars at the end of 1996," he said.
</P>
<P>
The reform package made by Secretary-General Kofi Annan does
not hold the immediate prospect of alleviating the U.N. financial
situation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
