<HEADLINE> US Deficit Expected Down to 23 billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congressional Budget
Office (CBO) said today that it expected a federal deficit in
fiscal 1997 of about 23 billion dollars, 11 billion smaller than
it estimated just a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The new estimate is the latest unexpectedly favorable twist in
a year that began with the Clinton administration and the CBO
projecting shortfalls of about 125 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The final figures for U.S. fiscal 1997, which ended September
30, should be available late this month.
</P>
<P>
The CBO said that the biggest reason for this year's shrinking
estimates has been unexpectedly high revenue collections.
</P>
<P>
But it said the declining of the U.S. government deficit seemed
to have little to do with the budget deal President Bill Clinton
and Congress enacted in August. The spending cuts in that measure,
which are aimed at eliminating all the U.S. federal deficits by
2002, will not take effect until 1998.
</P>
<P>
A 23-billion-dollar deficit would be the smallest since the 6
billion shortfall of 1974. The U.S. federal deficit hit a record
290 billion dollars in 1992 and the budget gap has shrunk every
year since President Clinton took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Last month, President Clinton's Office of Management and Budget
projected a deficit of 37 billion dollars in fiscal 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
