<DOCNO> XIE19971004.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Needs Transparency in Evaluating Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Former president of the
World Bank Robert MacNamara has urged the Tanzanian authorities
to be transparent in checking graft during the process of
privatizing parastatal organizations.
</P>
<P>
MacNamara, who was speaking to Parastatal Sector Reform
Commission (PSRC) officials in Dar es Salaam today, said
transparency would curb corruption especially at the stage of
evaluating bids.
</P>
<P>
Civil society should also be involved in bid evaluation
process, MacNamara, who is co-chairman of the Global Coalition
for Africa, told PSRC officials.
</P>
<P>
"Civil society should be active and well organized to address
various issues like corruption," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that experience has shown that corruption was rife
during the process of evaluation of bids and offers.
</P>
<P>
"I think you have very terrible problems, but please do not
misunderstand our views on this, " said the former world bank
president.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, briefing MacNamara and his delegation, PSRC Chairman
George Mbowe said the whole process of privatizing parastatal
organizations was one hundred percent transparent.
</P>
<P>
Mbowe said since the privatization process started in 1992, a
total of 158 parastatal organizations have been divestured,
earning the government 200 million US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission has listed a total of 308 such
organizations to be privatized. But he could not give projections
of the remaining public firms to be divestured.
</P>
<P>
The PSRC chief informed MacNamara and his delegation that a
number of public utilities, like telecommunications sector,
water, power company, harbors and railways would soon be
privatized.
</P>
<P>
He said strategic investors would soon buy 35 percent shares
in the telecommunications sector, while 20 percent other shares
would go to some institutions, few would be sold to local
institutions and the government would only retain 20 percent
shares.
</P>
<P>
On water sector, Mbowe said they have already identified four
firms which are interested in investing in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Mbowe said they have decided to invite investors in the water
and power sectors because of the urgency of the two sectors and
their importance in people's daily life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
