<HEADLINE> Shuttle Atlantis Separates from Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Shuttle Atlantis
separated from the Russian space station Mir today after six days
of linked flight during which the Mir was replenished with a new
central computer and a fresh American astronaut, the NASA's Space
Center in Houston said.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle slowly pulled away from Mir at 1:28 p.m. EDT (1728
GMT) as the spacecraft soared 250 miles (420 km) above
southeastern Russia, leaving David Wolf behind for a four-month
stay. His American predecessor, Michael Foale, was aboard Atlantis
to back Earth after a stressful four and a half month mission on
the Mir.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis arrived last weekend and brought for the Mir a new
central computer, spare batteries and repair equipment it needs
because of a collision with a cargo ship in June.
</P>
<P>
Undocking was delayed by one and a half hours to allow the Mir
crew time to replace a data-relay device that malfunctioned a
month ago and test a new one.
</P>
<P>
The electronics box provides data to the automatic docking
system that will be needed Tuesday for the arrival of an unmanned
resupply vessel.
</P>
<P>
The Mir crew has had trouble locating the punctures caused by
the crash, so NASA agreed to have the shuttle crew help out just
after undocking.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis is due back to Earth Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
