<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls for Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is calling for
the world's attention to the eradication of poverty, which has
become the "cornerstones of Ethiopia's development strategies and
democratic reforms."
</P>
<P>
Seyoum Mesfin, foreign minister of Ethiopia, said in his speech
at the 52nd session of the General Assembly that international
cooperation, whether through bilateral or multilateral means,
could not be a substitute for what individual countries must do to
ensure sustainable development and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
But it was critically important that the international economic
environment provided a level playing field, particularly for those
who had failed to put their countries on the track of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
He said the prediction that the level of poverty would continue
to grow in Africa was a challenge to the international community
as it reflected on the dire condition of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia had made important progress in building the basis for
food security for its people, he said. The country registered a 10
percent gross domestic product rate of growth in 1996. But there
could be no guarantee as long as production was totally dependent,
as in Ethiopia, on rain-fed agriculture.
</P>
<P>
On the debt relief measures outlined by some developed
countries, he said they found it difficult to meet conditions that
could not even be absorbed by far more advanced economies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
