<BODY>
<HEADLINE> St. Lucia Follows Majority of States in Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Saint Lucia has to shape
its foreign policy to meet the challenges in a changing world,
Prime Minister Kenny Anthony said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd session of the United Nations General
Assembly, he said, "The changing characteristics of the
international system have necessitated that we redefine the
boundaries of our alliances."
</P>
<P>
He said, "In this process, we must be guided by the imperative
of finding and mobilizing new sources of investment that are
predicated on creating new paths of sustainable growth."
</P>
<P>
"For us, foreign policy is about building bridges to other
people, other cultures and other markets," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Consistent with these basic principles, Saint Lucia has
proceeded in a direction which the majority of the states of the
world have already trod by establishing diplomatic links with the
People's Republic of China," Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
The East Caribbean nation established diplomatic relations with
the People's Republic of China on September 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the U.N. reform, the prime minister said his country
firmly believes that if the U.N. is to adequately address the
challenges of the coming century, it should become more responsive
to the needs of all its members states, especially the majority of
the member states' needs for sustainable development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
